Fo4br1pWQ3RR79N-TdT7lw.text: Most fantastic dogs around. Always a long line though so plan to take your time. Totally worth the wait.

8v2eCVJVBUYoFJBJbuA8Tw.text: A chain of hot dog restaurants based in Buffalo, New York. Founded in 1927 by Greek immigrant Theodore Spiro Liaros. Leave it to a Greek to build a chain that yelps praise with their highest accolade.  I am lunching on Teds signature footlong, fries and a coke. 7.5  And as I'm standing there John Belushi comes in to my mind shouting "cheeborger, cheeborger, cheeborger no pepsi coke."  Anyway they served up a delicious dog and fries today. Plus I got to read Teds hometown, Buffalo N.Y. newspaper. The Buffalo Bills are 2nd in the AFC East 4 wins 2 losses .667 3-0 at home 1-2 on the road.  Ted's is a must if you enjoy a charcoal grilled hot dog.

ZtpVxC5sSMucMGpO1G0Ueg.text: The hot dogs are similar to what you would have at a good back yard BBQ. This place is a bit overrated, nothing compared to Pinks or Wurstkuche in Los Angeles. The onion rings were the best item to get here.

ITfzi2xSr0HRJ_4tFgw8pQ.text: I've been going to this place for almost 10 years and they have always had a winning formula for their famous hot dogs and an easy meal. On work days, you need to get there before 11:30am or you'll be waiting an hour - they cook the sausages on a grill right in front of you - even though its sometimes 115 outside. Their home made shakes and onion rings are also a winner!

59NjpwItpPcCHw0ueTC1Ug.text: Choice of dogs.  Hot dogs have the skin casing which I love.  Onion rings were great.  Quick, Cheap (two dogs for under 6 bucks out the door)  It was exactly what I was looking for.  Fast, yummy, fair priced lunch.

dUct3KwNWo1roTpG1VgEIA.text: First time here (it's always busy every time I drive by, so I figured I would try it). The food is - delicious - fresh - & for a good price - will be back very soon!

X9wBQAoQqJRzfHnASlttyQ.text: We've been to Tod's Hot Dogs several times when in the area.  Simple menu so it is easier to decide!   Everything is charbroiled in front of your eyes.  Prices are reasonable.  The place is quite clean as are the restrooms.   Help is friendly.   All in all a nice place for a quick snack or dinner.

w4Wfxu46AlVoCcmGY5rBeQ.text: I was skeptical, but pleasantly surprised. The hot dogs were grilled to order and they had just about all of the condiments needed. I didn't try the Ted's Hot Sauce, which I will the next time I go.   There was a line, as many reviewers mentioned, but it went by pretty fast, Ted's kept it moving. We also got a table for 4 with no problem. Great place!

Tkmc0dVIvGnzpHQ8SDSFRQ.text: Can NOT rave enough about this place. I love it so much!! It's the only one in AZ which is awesome!! Line is out the door during lunch hours no matter what day...just goes to show how popular it is!

cOgEURWNV5E_ra-MCS2s8g.text: Ted's offered me a wonderously greasy medley in my stomach that was tasty until the very last bite.   Charred franks are my favorite way to enjoy them and Ted's didn't disappoint there. I ended up getting an all beef, a Polish and some onion rings (I had no idea how big an order of rings was). The links were grilled to near perfection and were quite juicy. As for the onion rings, they were greasy and sloppy and pretty much what most people would expect them to be. There is one downside though and that would be the lack of condiments. Don't get me wrong, there are a bunch but I was hoping for a lot more; there weren't even any grilled onions from what I saw. I had planned on getting my Polish Maxwell style, but alas, I could not.   There are two final things I would have to say. First, the food and the prices were great, and the sausages were very good. And second, I can strongly recommend this place but if Lobby's right down the road decided to do some charred dogs, I think business could be booming. Check out both places!

CSEjOkn4iDqPFlJbctRt0Q.text: Well..... I got chili and it was disgusting. It was full of grease. Like a 1/2 inch worth. How nasty. I am sitting here regretting eating it.. I need to work out now and have a glass of red wine. Ugh. The hot dog my man had was nothing great. Costco hot dogs are better and CHEAPER.

l7UY2oY9qXpinvvACgBiFQ.text: Who knew Hotdogs could have a cult following? Well they do at Ted's, a Tempe landmark. Try the Brats or Polish or Italian Sausage if you're ready for the next step up.

8S8F-mx9YSoLQ2Ea6nT5ZA.text: Hot Dogs!  you either love em or hate them.  I have to say Ted's are some of the best.  I always have the all beef and change up the toppings.  There are a lot of toppings to chose from and don't forget to order their onion rings or fries a plenty.  And their milkshakes are the best.  Ted's makes hot dogs awesome.  If you need a hot dog fix head over to Ted's.  Yes there will be a line, yes you will get to know the people around you and yes you will have an awesome experience.

cEnEiP-LvqRZjagpy1emUg.text: Visiting the Phoenix area, I wanted to try something that Phoenix yelpers raved about and Ted's Hot Dogs appeared with a 4-5 star rating from 7 yelpers!  We were excited about a place that serves up hot dogs and warrants five stars!  Even though they sold burgers and sandwiches, you have to order some type of sausage or dog when that's what they are famed for.  My friend and I opted for the Polish Sausage ($3.25), the BF chose the Bratwurst ($3.29), and my other friend went for their Regular Hot Dog ($2.05).  I read about their fabulous milkshakes, so chose a Chocolate Shake ($3.05) and their amazing Onion Rings ($2.59).  I requested all the sausages and dogs to be loaded up with everything, which looked like it included onions, peppers, a pickle spear, relish, ketchup, and mustard.  I must admit, they did look a bit smaller than what I'm used to.  And the cashier couldn't tell the difference between the Polish Sausage and the Bratwurst.  In terms of the hot dog, my friend was not impressed. He said the hot dog itself tasted like any other hot dog, but he did like all the fixings on top.  The polish sausage tasted a lot better than the bratwurst in my opinion.  You can see lots of spices and stuff in the polish sausage, but there wasn't enough kick for my tastes.  The chocolate milkshake was thick and made from real ice cream.  Their onion rings reminded me of an onion blossom because of their thin batter.  I wished they had a different kind of dipping sauce for it instead of ketchup.  Overall, my experience at Ted's Hot Dogs was just okay.  Maybe it's a locals thing and you have to be a True local to really appreciate their hot dogs and sausages.  I guess I just had a little more in mind.  Sidenote: Cash only  Total cost: Less than $19.00 (You can see the photo of everything we ordered in the business profile pics!)

q3IRN4fOJrKRH_emHTevDg.text: We just heard about Ted's from a friend, I'm really glad that we did. When we walked in, there was a pretty long line, which to me meant that we were in for a treat. I had the Bratwurst Dog, my wife had the all beef. We are both used to Chicago Style Dogs, these are very different. The way they are cooked on the grill, the way they are poked at by the cook, I really enjoyed it.   Try the onion rings, we liked those as well.   It has a very unique vibe, we will be back.

yOZJMTXuPdLdStgnJd4Muw.text: I have been in Arizona for 8 years and have driven past many times. We ordered a foot long chili dog and split, was a great eat and would recommend the place to anyone. If your girl wants a weiner other then yours then bring her there and watch her put that juicy piece of meat in her mouth, you won't be disappointed.

67SktFT1Z0M0lQMDbb5JaA.text: I thought this place was really good for what it is. I don't really understand all the awards and hype for it though... In the end it's just a hot dog to me. xFRsfg98zs_MPiHsKiPpaQ.text: Teds is awesome. The best onion rings ever.  There hot dogs are great and the service is so fast.

4XLPU78Rg4L3Y6c8asOjRg.text: If you are in the mood for a good hot dog then Ted's is a great choice.  It is cheap and friendly.  They also have a  great chicken sandwich and the french fries and onion rings are home made and to die for. So good. The only downside to this place is that ordering  can be a bit messy.  The cook hollars at you while you are still far back in the line and you have to yell your order at him and sometimes its crowded and hard to find a place to sit. aDw6z5AF-k4z-4pJZrvF7g.text: First time to Ted's was today. Been in Tempe eight years, and have been happy with Dave's Dog House but "frank (ly), moving "furter" on........ Certainly popular, long line, I had a good 20 min. wait. I ordered the all-beef chili dog, with added mustard and onions. Somewhat average, I must say. Did not get a lot of chili with the dog, and chili was a little too sweet for my taste. Bun, plain, out of the bag, but the charcoaled dog certainly has a great taste. Potato salad really grew on me though! Not bad, I may be back if in the area.

DKt7M1TPebEiD3nIV2nkvA.text: Obviously there have been a lot of great reviews of Ted's here. And this is not one of them. I was not blown away by my hot dog with mustard, onions and relish. It was ok. Honestly, I have made better ones. The relish tasted like the stuff out of the jar and the hot dog's flavor was nothing spectacular. Their fries are good, better than average. The onion rings are good, too, and better than average. The place has a great feel to it. From the food counter where you order and see your food prepared, to where it is handed off and they put whatever you want on your hot dog, sauerkraut, mustard, relish, onions, etc., to the memorabilia on the wall and the awards from the mid-80's for best hot dog place. But, I have to say, sorry Ted, it just wasn't that great. I would go back and eat there again, after all it wasn't bad. But I am not going to miss it if I don't make it back there ever again. There are plenty of places I have had a better dog, including Trader Joe's Fearless Franks grilled at home. Call me a hot dog snob, but Ted's just didn't cut the mustard.

nOeGMnKtZZzz40h5izeMXg.text: My experience with Ted's was not a good one this time around.  It had been years since I had been  there  and I was not all that impressed back then.  It did not even make it on my "if I'm ever in the neighborhood again" list.  But recently I had a craving for a hot dog and decided to try Ted's again.  I ordered a hot dog a  brat and a side of potato salad.  The hot dog was average at best.  The brat was RAW on the inside and inedible.  And the potato salad was completely tasteless and most of the potato's were hard from not being cooked long enough.  Even though I did not have a good experience I'm still not ready to check them off my list.  Although I will never drive from Phoenix to Ted's JUST for a hot dog like I did this last time I will at least give them one more shot if I'm ever in the area again.

dYHT4XG5X7n9Dkul3ENH2w.text: I used to live next door to Ted's and I had to have it at least once a week. The hot dogs are fantastic, the onion rings are delicious, corn dogs are superb. Fries could be better though. Only downside: They only accept cash so a ER trip to the ATM may be in order.

aTwIDJ88HjmRRUkOfP9EHA.text: I'll keep it simple. Best hot dogs I've had in my life. Grilling the dog make all the difference in the world. I've been to the famous Pinks in LA and this place is way better.

-naTpaMTcUr8FiZNMTfQmQ.text: I'm not sure why you'd rate Ted's lower than this. Being a native, there are few local places that have such good hot dogs as Ted's. Clean place, good price, order your dogs how you like them. Delicious and definitely a Tempe go-to for quick, good food.

3EO9Cy0_kYk1ydBTayX_yg.text: I came to Ted's last week to meet up with the lunch UYE group, but I was a little late and they were on their way out.  So, I waited in the line, alone, to order a dog to go.  The funny thing, they call to you from behind the grill to place your order.  As they were calling for my attention, I looked around over my shoulder as if to say, "Oh, you're talking to me" when the cook was calling for my attention... haha, that's something you should look out for so you're not caught off guard if its your first time around the block.  I got the beef dog with ketchup, mustard and a pickle.  They grill the hot dog on an open flame.  The dogs don't taste "grilled" enough for my tastes, but it was ok.  I really enjoyed the onion rings that I ordered on the side.  Very tasty.    I won't miss this place if I don't go back.  But if someone wants to go, I'll meet them there.  No problem.

vmvV0xJLrzyGcnGGLjY9hg.text: Im so sorry Portillos I didn't mean to stray. Believe me it will not ever happen again!!   The service was ridiculous. They have no rhythm and the onion ring guy apparently didn't hear my order so we had to wait for those. The onion rings were the only thing good!  I threw my hotdog away. I took one bite and after tasting the dry bun I decided to eat no bun. Couldn't do it. Threw it away.   My bad never again. Should have just gone to Costco for a $1.50 dog n pepsi. At least I could get a refill.

vEF05fusG3WXCox1g_a_Xw.text: I've been wanting to try the Ted's in Tempe after stumbling upon it when visiting the Buffalo, NY area. I was shocked to hear them say "we have a location in Tempe!". Since then, it's been on my list to go and we finally did.  They have a lot of options for their dogs, and even for those who want to get a burger. If you're going to a hotdog place, I'm not sure why you'd want a burger, but hey people are weird these days. They also had a vegetarian option, which is cool for you healthy folks. I got their jumbo dog with lettuce, tomato, onion, hot sauce and pickles. If it sounds like a lot, it is, but that's what makes it great. Tons of options and ways to turn your average dog into a top-notch dog. They also had excellent fries and onion rings for sides.   Overall, lots of options, tasty food and a pretty decent price. You could have a nice meal for under $6 if you wanted to. That's always a big plus! I'll definitely try to make it back there if I'm in that part of town.

uBr9swiLqosgeKkGBdQviA.text: So you know how you crave hot dogs like a couple times a year?  Yeah... well it was America's birthday and we were craving a hot dog - I had already tried Portillo's and this was on my short list of places that were semi-close AND open on the 4th.    I got the bacon wrapped (Sonoran) jumbo dog and had a bite of their cheeseburger.  The dog had the snap I wanted (natural casing) and was flavorful and juicy - just like I had hoped.  Tried a sip of the Loganberry shake and that was fresh and tasty.  We weren't the only ones who had this thought, as the place does not accept phone in orders and the line was quite long... but once I got to the counter the service was pretty good and by the time we got home the food was still warm.  Next year when I'm craving a good dawg, I'll come back!

h0brNf2PazS9VM2VjLLFnw.text: After reading help reviews,  I thought we'd have to try it.  Ugh..I wish we hadn't.  The service was so so... the food was ehhhh... the only things worth mentioning were the shake and the riot beer float

rOGgKOP0btJ04WynC0KT6Q.text: I grew up coming to Ted's and would always bring family and friends when they were here from out of town. Today I went in for lunch and was amazed by all the new changes. It looked great at first glance. The menu has all these crazy options like Macaroni and Cheese Hotdog and a sea dog. They now take your order on an iPad instead of calling out like the old way. The line moved extremely slow as people tried to decide over the new menu and the employee tried to work the new technology. As we inched our way through the line the employees eyes were fixated at the new order screens and were too busy to have any customer interaction. We finally got our food and made our way to the once huge seating area that used to be full of booths. The seating area has now been replaced by cheap dollar shore chairs and tables. Not sure where the rest of the people in line plan to sit since there is very minimal seating now. Wish they would of kept the original Ted's. If it wasn't broke then don't fix it! I'll have to find a new spot to bring out of town visitors now.

jRVQisCLw0-gv1DbCciZ-A.text: I tried this place EVERYONE talks about..here in AZ... you hear "best toppings" the "Flavor" the "NY imported Hotdogs"...Puh-leez. I thought it was OK. That is all.   I say you save ur money and go get a SONORAN HOT Dog  and then tell me about Flavor, Toppings and who needs imported hotdogs when you can make a normal hotdog a mexican deliciousness??? Shoot I'll make you a bomb Hotdog Myself!  Ayyy dios mio...Not impressed.

WkxVUcDMX_441R4GfW123Q.text: Extremely frustrating to wait in like for 15-20 minutes only to have my order completely wrong. I ordered a veggie dog, which I've had before and IS vegetarian. All of the wait (really unnecessary there were 4-5 people working the grill and 2 people in line in front of me) just to come home and have a real hot dog that I'm unable to eat (I'm a vegetarian.)   Not going to be coming back to Ted's.

rF3af8XwnrFiy9IfHjDmRQ.text: Wasn't impressed with the chili cheese dog. The cheese they use is your standard melted plastic looking nacho cheese. Very flavorless chili too.  Four dogs and a small tea cost me $16...kinda pricey and I expected more.

c6ap3rMXCo91QZ4amPt7NA.text: There has never been a time where I regret standing in the massive line to get my jumbo burger.

iAXqpiRhIWbaukjJwNSwIg.text: Food and service are both amazing! The quality is always consistently great. Whenever I'm in the area around lunchtime I can't help but stop in, but be sure to be early because it gets packed around noon. My favorite is the Brat with peppers and onions

P8FAhLLMmUXotdqnx_umuw.text: Ok so the vegetarian went into the hot dog shop...  My friends dig this place quite a bit. I can even admit to liking the old school vibe of the place.  The staff are friendly although they do roll their eyes at ordering a "veggie dog" sometimes, but that is probably involuntary so we'll let it slide.  There always seems to be a line but it's not too bad of a wait to get your food. I have to give them props for having a vegetarian option for those of us who still like to hang out with meat eating friends.  The "veggie" dogs are cooked with the other meat so if you are super strict vegetarian then you may want to skip it. I do not have those qualms so I get mine with the homemade hot sauce and cheese.  They are pretty good for a veggie dog and oddly authentic tasting. Nothing to write home about, but hey what can you do? They have two excedingly awesome things if the meat or "veggie" dogs freak you out, the onion rings and the milk shakes.  Try: - Onion Rings "Crispy" - Milk Shakes

T7xuU6dJXm0PiAzXR8leDA.text: Everything was made fresh to order. The staff was incredibly friendly and the food was excellent! Great lunch spot.

lF0nksO20kEwNnTQC2t0kA.text: YUM! I got a hot dog with Mac and cheese on top, so good! And my boyfriend got relish, catsup, mustard, the usual on his. We both thoroughly enjoyed the hot dogs as well as the french fries so much!  However any of the packaged food like the potato salad we got was small, overpriced, and bleh. Just buy at the grocery store.  And be prepared for a wait. They make it as you order, but there is always a looong line!

phvl6uvdJPtYrukLJYepuw.text: Freshly made while you wait.  Grilled on a grill.  Watching them prepare it was interesting.  Very filling and delicious.

photos.caption: Photo of Ted's Hot Dogs - Tempe, AZ, United States. Our late lunch early dinner cost just under 17.00.
Photo of Ted's Hot Dogs - Tempe, AZ, United States. Our order is Italian sausage, regular hot dog, and a chili cheese dog with freshly made onion rings.
Photo of Ted's Hot Dogs - Tempe, AZ, United States. More newspaper article framed.

g1zlLX_6G_bChEAUa-ULVQ.text: I did not have high expectations of this place, especially since everyone raves about Portillos and it was just so-so.  I was pleasantly surprised to find that the hot dogs are fantastic! They're grilled in front of you, perfectly charred, and so juicy and delicious.  They also have bratwurst and polish sausage on the menu I will definitely try a bratwurst next time. My husband doesn't like hot dogs ( aka composite meat ) so he had a hamburger instead.  He said it was good and he'd  order it again. The servings of french fries and onion rings were  big enough to share. The onion rings were good and crispy, not too greasy and fries are good too.   The only downside was the seating. The booths are "set" meaning there's no way to adjust the table closer for little kids, and if you're tall, you'll have to fold yourself into the booth which is a little uncomfortable. Other than that this was a great experience!

yFo0khQvNO7T_h4Bi2WffQ.text: Hotdogs were good nothing really special about hotdogs anyway, but great mac n cheese.

photos.caption: Photo of Ted's Hot Dogs - Tempe, AZ, United States

23PGUkA51nwQkDLgX3_WgA.text: Very good hot dogs. These beauties are charcoal grilled so they have that authentic family picnic taste. I ordered a footlong chili cheese dog with the bun grilled and an order of onion rings. The hot dogs were great and the onion rings were dynamite. Everything is made in front of you, so no soggy dogs here! Whenever I'm back in this area, I'll be coming to Ted's.

photos.caption: Photo of Ted's Hot Dogs - Tempe, AZ, United States. Footlong Chili Cheese Dog w/ Onion Rings

plZQfrKGRLxUEOBo0Nwa0w.text: Ted's seems to take great pride in it's hot dogs. It's a cool, little spot in Tempe. I wasn't overly impressed with the footlong hot dog I'd ordered, and the orange cream shake was okay. Next time I'll try an all-beef dog and see if makes me love this place as much as others seem to. I'm giving it four stars for now; my next visit could tip it in either direction.

BLgWfrkoh7DTzo0qt6rQpg.text: Still as good as ever! While nothing will compare to that first visit, the food is still just as good as the first day I went last summer. I've been maybe 5-6 times since then, and I've never been disappointed. My favorite place to go for lunch in the summertime! I am sad that they changed their menu boards to be more modern, no more of the sliding letter-type boards of yesteryear :(

MURJRdW8lnDppY7Sk8DmrA.text: Still trying to figure out what the big deal is about this place.  Onion rings were good, so I'll give them that.  Had a foot long and a regular chili dog.  Foot long was average pretty much in every way.  Bun was slightly stale and hard.  Chili dog was average.  Chili was below average.  Diet Dr Pepper was more soda water than Dr Pepper.  If you measure all hot dogs on the planet on straight line continuum with the $1.50 Costco special being the mid point, I'm not sure this place measures up to the mid point.  One other thing...$12 bucks and change for a foot long, chili dog, onion rings and a soda...YIKES!!!  But then again, maybe I just don't get it.  2.5 wasn't a choice, but 3 is to high.

ONa2PJ_b_vOrfYvJj4YD9A.text: Nothing special here. Being from New England I expect a hot dog joint to carry a large variety of dogs and buns. This place was just like any other. Here are my disappointments.  1. No New England style buns. They didn't even know what they are and the cook looked at me funny. To me this is insane, the bun is the second most important part next to the type of hot dog. A cheap potato bun doesn't cut it.  2. I asked for my bun to be buttered and toasted, again they were unable to do this and looked at me funny again.  3. I wanted my dog boiled and charred, again they don't do this. I am okay with boiled dogs and would have gone that route but they didn't even offer them boiled! Head scratcher on that one.  4. The only natural casing dog they carried came as a foot long. I did order this and it was good. I wish they carried natural casing dogs in regular size as I was not too happy with the price of having to order a foot long.  5. Service was slow, not friendly and they seemed rather irritated I asked question. Also ordering was confusing with all the people behind the counter you would think someone would want to take my order. They must not be that hungry for money.  On one positive I did enjoy the onion rings. They kind of reminded me of the ones served at Wahlburgers in Hingham Ma.  Any case, if you are from New England be prepared to be disappointed. I had high hopes seeing this was a franchise from New York, but then again New York is not part of New England.  Late,

N5_UtwCQinntxYaC_eexjw.text: They have the best onion rings. I don't even like onion rings but I always order Ted's onion rings.

ZyqkExRYBml4HwRxjq2feA.text: I have been going to Teds since I was a little girl! I have always loved their foot longs with cheese and cheese fries! They are amazing. It's a little slow in the like but they can't help it! It's still so amazing. I make my husband go every week.

mrvV1lM3SxW6ouFqOUdl-A.text: The assortment of hot dogs and sausages here are great.  As long as you don't stray off the dog menu, you are golden.  The onion rings are very bland, steer clear of those.  The Burgers are pretty simple as well.  But the sausages, oh the sausages!  The All Beef Hot Dog and the Italian Sausage are excellent, well worth the wait.  The Polish, corn dog and regular dogs are good, but not quite the bang of the Italian or All Beef.  The chili is decent, not very spicy at all, so maybe get some hot sauce on the side to add if you like your chili with some zing.  Overall, I definitely love this place, and will be a regular.  Once I have tried everything a few times, I will settle into a routine of delicious dogs and sausages.

62meGUS0MP7GugwZ5x8l6Q.text: The food here is really good! Can't beat a Chicago style hot dog grilled right in front of you.

9xQpgwsuJsN77tuz6mTUqA.text: would be 5 stars but am limited on when I can go as the lines are always out the door, and sadly I am handicapped and standing in the line I can not do as they have no seating while waiting :( .  The fact though that there is always a line there speaks volumes of how good their food is. I am not a big Hotdog fan myself but their  Hamburgers are excellent cooked over a mesquite wood grill YUM. If there is no line I will stop and grab a Onion Ring they are soooo good its a rare treat because as I said so busy normally, Just had some last week as I went by right as they opened and pulled in so fast I left rubber on the street.  If you are looking for great Hotdogs, Hamburgers, Fries (get them with cheese) and Onion rings this is the place to stop long wait but so worth it. If you are handicapped and can not stand to long go when they open it is worth it.

GzxKdZT2wicpqAVCGTIs8g.text: It doesn't take long to realize that there are a lot of Midwest transplants living in the valley. It's evident in all the Chicago based restaurants that have a presence to the Cubs fan base at spring training games... But who knew western New York was represented in the mix?  Buffalo to be specific. I don't know as much about the New York - Phoenix connection. But it's both quirky and cool to think that the only Ted's Hot Dogs outside of the state of New York, is in Tempe.  After hearing the ads on the radio forever, I finally visited Ted's for the first time about a year ago. Since then, I've also introduced my sons. And tonight, I was feeling like a kid with a craving for a good ole messy chili dog. As always, I wasn't disappointed.  I have previously enjoyed a variety of their hot dogs and the burger I tried was delicious too. I wanted something different so I chose a jumbo chili and cheese dog. The hot dogs are cooked over charcoal. 'Nuff said. I added chopped onion, mustard and extra chili. The cheese is a cheddar cheese sauce. Perfect for this messy kind of affair!  As always, I chose the excellent hand made onion rings. This side is best shared. They are cut thin and the portion is generous. Trust me, if you like onion rings, you won't be disappointed. Or feel like you got ripped off cause there was five rings in the bag. Finally, I chose the orange cream milkshake for my beverage/dessert. I don't think I've ever tried an orange shake before. It was delicious and refreshing.  Thankfully, Ted's isn't all about hot dogs. There is enough variety to bring me back. Next time, I'll be enjoying either the triple cheeseburger I saw being promoted, or a foot long, or one of their white hots. Thanks Ted's! Now I have to start acting my age again...

photos.caption: Photo of Ted's Hot Dogs - Tempe, AZ, United States. Two delicious bacon cheeseburgers, a split (fries &amp; rings) and some milkshakes!
Photo of Ted's Hot Dogs - Tempe, AZ, United States. Lots &#39;O&#39; Rings, Chili Cheese Dog and an Orange Cream Milkshake. All on a clever charcoal grill tray liner.

kSFa2CTm7giNwbM6t3QQJQ.text: I'm from Buffalo and grew up on Teds.  I drop in Tempe location whenever I'm in town.  Sahlen dogs are awesome.

aLF-Ft8sDdXjzinnnEz0Qw.text: For me, Ted's is nostolgia, remembering a childhood favorite food and the company of my grandparents in Tonawanda, NY. I hadn't had Ted's in almost 20 years, but luckily, work brought me to Phoenix and I made it down to the one Ted's location outside of NY. I was not disappointed. The hot dogs are as good as my childhood memories and I finally fulfilled a childhood dream of eating a footlong! The fries, onion rings, and shake were good, but nothing special. The star here is the charbroiled hot dog. If you're craving a a great hot dog or you want to take visit through childhood memories of NY, Ted's is the place.

photos.caption: Photo of Ted's Hot Dogs - Tempe, AZ, United States. Neat area for Buffalo newspapers!
Photo of Ted's Hot Dogs - Tempe, AZ, United States. Footlong Hot Dog of my childhood aspirations!

4xiTaVIMExTmg9PiHkZftg.text: Awesome place. So delicious. I got a grilled chicken sandwich to be a little healthier and my boyfriend got 2 hot dogs which were killer. Onion rings were crispy and delicious and staff was very friendly. Easy five stars.

qzqF5pz9Ek0ePMsaXDPDig.text: Kids didn't want to eat the poke bowl so they ordered from here.  I have eaten here a couple times for lunch.  The hot dogs are good. Their specialty is that it is grilled right in front of you. You have a choice of several toppings like cheese and bacon and the normal ketchup and mustard.  They offer burgers, fries, and onion rings which I think are pretty good.  The regular dogs are pretty large but you can order the foot longs if you are hungry.  There are also other dogs that you can order if you don't want the beef dog.  Prices are a little high for hot dogs but go ahead and check it out.

photos.caption: Photo of Ted's Hot Dogs - Tempe, AZ, United States. Checkin in.  Whew, that&#39;s hot.
Photo of Ted's Hot Dogs - Tempe, AZ, United States. Bacon and cheese hotdog...tasty.

yo4_ec_JAXtscKqSx8suNA.text: Buffalo regular and jumbo beef hot dogs. Allegedly the best hot dogs. I like jumbo beef one for sure. The price is pretty economic. We drove half an hour here just want to have a few hot dogs for dinner.

photos.caption: Photo of Ted's Hot Dogs - Tempe, AZ, United States
Photo of Ted's Hot Dogs - Tempe, AZ, United States

RHxitzeOKbWfLLNeCQ6HBw.text: Who knew you could do so much with a hot dog??  These guys have to be doing something right to have been in business so long, and the tasty hot dog I ate backed up that theory all the way from hungryville to fat-and-happy town.   I think these guys must be the only people who still cool on actual charcoal inside a restaurant. They seem to have a pretty tight system going where they get your order and start it going so that by the time you get to the cashier your order is ready to go. I did feel like it was a little crowded in the kitchen, with staff kinda falling over each other, but the food came out quickly and tasting good. So whatever works.  They did get the order a little wrong, but it was lunchtime and packed, so not the end of the world.   Glad I visited - felt like I got a small slice of what 1950s hot dog America was like :)

photos.caption: Photo of Ted's Hot Dogs - Tempe, AZ, United States. Bacon and cheese jumbo and a jumbo with relish, mustard and ketchup. And a split side of onion rings and chips

Mnpp56CV8Sa7_e9jCuLVrg.text: Great place for a charbroiled hot dog. They do not grill it until you order it. Staff was very friendly. They actually talked to you and even gave you a smile. Their milkshakes are sooooo good. I was in love. The hot dog was tasty too. You can get a full meal at Ted's. I enjoy the vintage pictures on the wall along with the 50's/60's music. Fun place to eat and remember the times.   Very clean restaurant plus there is always a line which means the food is good.

hQFP4gF_pU83Ehds7fC9hA.text: Went just after 4pm... business was slow and the line was even slower... stood there for over 10min, only two people ahead of us. The line didn't budge. My son and I left.

vjNMVCALesQ5pIL8cUzoXw.text: This is the GOAT. If you're anywhere within driving distance it's well, well worth the trip. I can't think of a better hot dog and I've been all over the country. The onion rings are amazing and even the cheeseburger is as good as you'll get. It's not pricey and it's all cooked right in front of you. I really can't recommend it enough, one of my favorites.

um7H4DiGzIxBs00OBUDAvQ.text: Updated 9/13/17...  Changed from 4 stars to three. Double cheese burger has thin patties; meat is ok. Water is not filtered... you do the math on that one. We just couldn't drink it or the ice cubes. Only one size on shakes. On the upside, they have remodeled since we were last hear. Great job on spiffing the place up.  Previous review:  Fabulous New York style hot dogs, brats, sausages, burgers, chicken sandwiches. They grill it right there in front of you and add all kinds of toppings. French fries rock.  4 stars because onion rings are incredibly greasy and comes in a big bag of gnarley pieces. Also, you can't fill your own soda or water or put on your own mustard and stuff. The young people running the counter aren't the most professional. Maybe that's kind of closer to how they would do it in NYC.   Shakes are yummy - choices are chocolate, vanilla or strawberry. This beats Portillo's hot dogs down the street any day. Yea for Ted's!

0hmVnadvmPvHIQgdHSsTjQ.text: This is one of the worst places to get a burger or hot dog. They flagged my last review and had it taken down because it was too honest. They make you stand around and wait forever and the quality is far from acceptable. I'd try Portillos or Culver's over this place any day.

photos.caption: Photo of Ted's Hot Dogs - Tempe, AZ, United States. $8.10 for double with bacon... backyard bbq level quality at best.
Photo of Ted's Hot Dogs - Tempe, AZ, United States. Burnt bacon and government cheese. Some like it, others like when food is good.

NexPjnDzoCQ8uUEcRqw9XA.text: I lived in Chicago 62 years.  Always had jobs outside for the most part which took me into every neighborhood in Chicago.  I have had the best, Vienna Hot Dogs, the king of hot dogs in the Windy City. Places that you wonder what was in the bun. Hundreds of hot dog joints since I was a kid. This was my first visit to Teds, toying with the thought of continuing on to my beloved Portillo's . But no, had to try Teds.   I was not disappointed.  Was a GREAT DOG! Buffalo you gotta be proud of your Teds.   Had a regular with mustard, relish, onion, tomato and a pickle, a chili cheese dog. Loved it.

0jIkll1Ez8SxZeVwTR6PLA.text: I'll pass on Ted's...not sure what the rave is about--maybe the name and the length of time they've been open. It was crazy packed and the line wrapped around--with one register there has to be a more efficient way. We likely spent 20 minutes just in line. I'm not a fan of their sweet but not so tasty chili. Their milkshake was good and the spilt was okay they were lukewarm so couldn't get the full effect. I'll stick with Detroit Coney Island down on Broadway...great chilli dogs!   However, customer friendly and very kind staff!!! And clean!!!! That is hard to come by.

hFhWNtbIcXXgC04CbkfmhA.text: Buffalo hot dogs in Arizona? YES PLEASE! We were so excited that there was a Ted's in Phoenix. If you haven't been yet you need to stop by and try out one of their delicious hot dogs. They're cooked perfectly and have that tell tale snap as you bite into them. You can top them with pretty much anything you could want and they have loganberry as a choice for drinks- perfect combo! I also grabbed their mac and cheese and it is just like Stouffer's which I happen to love.   The best part was that Buffalonians flock here. While we were in line at least three other Buffalo natives stopped in to get their hot dog fix. It was really fun to talk with some of the Phoenix and Buffalo locals about how crazy different the weather is from climate to climate and you can tell that Ted's isn't just about the food, it also brings the community together and sparks conversations.  Come to Ted's you'll be happy you did!!

V9TAWSS4f_3fT4tvj1pFFg.text: Gross highly expensive glob of fried onions.  Supposed to be onion rings.  Almost  $5 for this greasy mess.

photos.caption: Photo of Ted's Hot Dogs - Tempe, AZ, United States

gaWk5tI3-us_sc3YY9Q8Zw.text: Been dying to check out Ted's after hearing raving reviews from many friends. The branding and history of Ted's is really cool and the space is filled with awesome typography and old photos of the companies history. On my visit they played a ton of 50's music and the employee energy was great. They have a broad assortment of topping options and everything is grilled right in front of you. If you're craving a good hot dog this is one of the best I've had! Will be going again next time I travel to Phoenix!

Photo of Ted's Hot Dogs - Tempe, AZ, United States

y9lDxA_BGKbrE-fcrAnXMQ.text: Meh. I have a hard time giving more than two stars to any place that has flies constantly buzzing around indoors while you're trying to eat. The cheeseburger and fries I had were very average, I wouldn't go out of my way to eat here again.

f41UNzOHTnbuERnyXJ0P9g.text: I do not get to Ted's often enough.  Been going there for 20 years, Today had the polish with all the fixins and the greatest onion rings in the Valley.  Teds is a Tempe staple.  If you have not been there, you need to get there soon.

1DoLdNhoItTJPUphSFFe9A.text: They closed for a while and did a nice job at updating the inside. It looks brighter and cleaner. But I must say they still have the worst most pissed off looking workers ever. They all just stare at you with a look of F U in their eyes. The way you order is weird. No one knows where to line up and it causes issues. You order. When your dog is ready you have to work your way back through all the people standing in line or shout at them what you want. Ice machine was empty and they looked mad I told them so. I don't get the love of this place. My meal was 10 and honestly not worth the headache.

DNZUG2cLGi9hhaPqRFiC4Q.text: The 4 star rating must have set my expectations too high. But in comparison to other hot dog places it's not all that great either.   Better than the nasty chain weinerschnitzel, but not as good portillo's or coney's grill.   I also tried the Mac and cheese which was kinda gross, especially since a box of Velveeta shells & cheese outshines it.   The Fries are fine, service was very polite, pricing fair. But with so many choices for a hot dog in the area. Meh I'll pass.

hCHrNXEKtQXqhxv0TwabWA.text: There is a restaurant in the Seattle, WA. area called Dick's Drive-in.  Ted's reminds me of Dick's, because they offer greasy, standard fare at an affordable price.  I expected the food to be better, but wasn't too disappointed.  Ted's doesn't mess around with fancy fixins' or strange combinations.  I assumed their motto to be: "If it ain't broke, don't fix it."  You can screw up a hot dog if you over-think it, but Ted's has stayed True to the tradition.  On second thought, I bet their motto is: "Keep it simple, stupid."  Also, their onion rings are pretty damn good: slim, flaky crust, with a sweet tasting onion.

NxCpSfQld0EbzNX7_wCTzQ.text: I love that they now offer GF buns! Their grilled dogs and brats are the BEST in Phoenix by far.  Love stopping here whenever I'm in Tempe. Cannot get grilled dogs like this anywhere else in the Valley, wish you had more locations. A dog just tastes better when grilled. For me the darker the better. Just a couple words of advice to the workers- use a knife to cut the GF hot dog buns instead of trying to use your gloved fingers, you'll have better results. Also just change gloves before handling my GF bun without asking me if I want you to :) I think most GF peeps would agree with me on this.

d0-Ot2sOS9L-1Qp5058O3A.text: When I knew I was moving from Buffalo to Phoenix I was pumped to know I could still get a Ted's fix. Many locations around WNY, and I believe this is the only one outside the area. Love the Buffalo decor and you can even read the Buffalo News. Now the food: best hog dogs (Sahlens) in this area for me (not into the Chicago style and haven't given Sonoran a fair shot.) they have added a lot to their menu over time, but I stick with the classics- regular dog, regular cheeseburger (everything on them), fresh cut rings, and Loganberry. The hot sauce is dynamite and they sell it by the jar. Feel like I'm back in Buffalo when I'm in this place, thanks Ted

DnpAbmiv5I_mFn-Pg8wJ1Q.text: Every so often, a place reminds you of what True quality means. I get that to some people it's "just a dog" or "just a sausage" but to the yelper/foodies out there, TRUST AND BELIEVE THAT TED'S IS THE REAL DEAL.  I've been coming here since the 90's - White Hots, Italians, All Beefs, Brats, Chili Dawgs...whatever your pleasure, Reds will hook you up.   Fries, onion rings, shakes - ALL also legit.   If ya don't know, now y'know...

N30ExYS81IX-jg2jhQYLaA.text: Update: When I submitted a review to the manager of Ted's about our horrible experience, they were extremely responsive and nice about it, which I really appreciated. They offered a gift card to give them another chance, and we accepted. We just went in again today, and it was a much more pleasant experience. The workers were nice, but not overly friendly, which is perfectly fine with me. They smiled and took the order respectfully, and the entire order was complete and correct the first time. The food was yummy and we got it decently quickly. I noticed that the had a new sign that clarified the sauce options, which was not there before, and I suspect my complaint may have been the reason for that. I am boosting the review to a 3 instead of a 1 because of this. I would make it a 3.5 if I could. We still have money on the gift card, so when I go back again I may raise the stars again. I'm not sure if it was just an improvement in training or if the workers are just nicer during lunch hours (when there aren't high school kids working?). Either way, it felt just like a nice, normal experience instead of being treated horribly, and that was a HUGE improvement to me.

G227JAZU8ZY3r6JVM2tsJQ.text: My review in June just after the remodel opening of Ted's was based on what appeared to be a very poor quality of furnishings. The owner informed me that it was temporary until new furnishings arrived. Perhaps signs posted to alert patrons of that fact would have been helpful and also, perhaps waiting until the proper furnishings had arrived before opening might have given a better first impression of the remodel. I don't think customers would have complained if it took a little longer to completely finish the job properly. The quality of their hot dogs and burgers is still excellent.

BvuZQQ639h6eKtpkImgn3w.text: finally went. My mother was craving a chili dog while we were out one day so we decided to go for lunch. I wish that I enjoyed it as much as most other people seem to.   Food wasn't what I thought that it would be. I thought that the hot dogs were okay, nothing special and not worth the price---I've had better from the grocery store and cooked on the grill at home.  My mother didn't like the chili and I didn't care for the sauerkraut that I had on my bratwurst. The onion rings were decent though.  The decor is cute and makes you feel like you've been pulled back in time and out East. Now this is where the big problem starts...  The service is just horrible. I encountered four different people working there and only one smiled, another asked me what I wanted and then snapped at me for "ordering incorrectly" (like I know how you're "supposed" to order at a place that I've never been to?)  and the last girl was breaking all kinds of health code violations. Seeing her play with her hair and drinking her personal drinks with her GLOVES ON and then touching food disgusted me. Maybe that played a role in why I didn't think the food tasted that great...because of the people who were handling it. I threw out most of my food, honestly.  I'm usually willing to give a place a second chance if I have an off first visit but I honestly don't ever see myself going back to Ted's. Gross.

LQTtylgTvUdFFCp0uek-xQ.text: The food is delicious & the atmosphere fun! If you're a hot dog & burger lover like myself, I would highly recommend checking this place out! They grill your food right in front of you & you can pick out exactly what toppings you want. It's a good price for the quality & portions you get & really very affordable! Because of the ordering style be prepared to wait a little bit while the food is cooked & the guests ahead of you pick out their toppings. As long as you're not in a hurry, next time you have a hot dog or burger craving this is the place to go!

5NdcgAY9ACZh7Ib3jbGucg.text: I have gone to Ted's many times now and each time I get the foot long hot dog with classic fixings. This time around I tried the double burger, it was good, a typical homemade style burger, but Ted's really shines with their hot dogs/bratwursts.  The onion rings are hand made and are the prefect form of flaky that the don't feel like I'm eating a pound of grease. The fries are delicious and when salted a little and paired with a rich, cold ketchup, you can't go wrong. The only downside is that the lines are really long everytime I have gone, but I guess thats what you have to deal with when everyone wants to eat at Ted's.

photos.caption: Photo of Ted's Hot Dogs - Tempe, AZ, United States. Ted&#39;s locations in both New York and Arizona

TNp542kz0ROOzlviL6wa-w.text: Maybe because the of the large amount of hype and the ridiculously long line, we had unrealistically high hopes. Needless to say, we were disappointed when we finally sat down to eat. Well, I would not prefer these over wienersnitzel. They didn't wow.   The service was meh. I was jazzed and told them I have lived in the valley for 17 years and have driven by and always thought  I should try that place someday...I announced that today was the day and what should I have. They acted as though I was an idiot. They may be right but humor me and recommend something or at least make me glad I decided to visit. They were just like shrug, shrug, meh.  Whatever, they're fine. Nothing special. I will probably drive by for another 17 years.

rCbLEfoLhUCK5wZ8vqIAew.text: Our family enjoyed the wide variety of hot dogs (think mac and cheese dog) from the world famous Ted's Hot Dogs. Not only was the food good, but it was a fun place to hang out and eat.

i4jz3Ve02g_hlqxhK-djyQ.text: After getting tired of waiting for a table at a local breakfast joint, my husband and I decided to jet and go some place else.  What better way to start the day than with hot dogs!  The place was busier than I had expected at 11am, but not to the point where there was no place to sit.  It seemed to get busier as we were waiting in line to order.    Everything is cooked right in front of you on a charcoal grill (with real flames and everything, folks - no simulated grilling).  You order what you want, it is cooked, and then you are asked what you want on it, sort of like a Qdoba setup.  My husband ordered the footlong with mustard, ketchup, onion, and pickles, a side of onion rings, and a chocolate shake.  I decided to go for the mac and bacon dog, a small fry, and a chocolate malt.  Our total came to $21, which may seem like a lot for hot dogs, but the amount of food we ended up with was pretty intense.  Most places that I've gotten onion rings at seem to go light on how many they give you.  At this place we could have forfeited the side of fries and still had extra onion rings left over.  A plus for us was that they were beer battered rather than breaded.  The fries looked to be freshly cut as they had skin on the ends, but they were pretty average.  My husband's footlong was topped with a generous amount of the requested toppings, including two full pickle spears.  My mac and bacon dog was loaded with macaroni and cheese, onion, and two strips of bacon.  They grill the bacon instead of frying it, which gives it a really good flavor.  My chocolate malt seemed a little more melted than I would have preferred, but I think some of that has to do with it being put into a paper cup and this being Arizona in August.  The only weird thing that I observed here was that none of the employees seemed to be in a very good mood.  They were pleasant enough, never rude, but none of them cracked a smile even once.  It didn't seem like any of them were particularly happy about being there.  Overall though it was a good experience, the food was tasty, and it was quick.

photos.caption: Photo of Ted's Hot Dogs - Tempe, AZ, United States. Footlong, mac &amp; bacon dog, onion rings, and a small fry.  The breakfast of champions!

DFqJ094oCwm8rxdyT1e-AA.text: Pros:  good quality meat and flavorful toppings  Cons: $5 for a medium sized chili dog is a little pricey.  They need to pile on the toppings but they don't.   Worth a try....

dAFN6VpiJnzUANKzhCkBBQ.text: Maybe it was an "off" night, but I just went here with my family and the experience leaves me wondering if I'll ever go back.  The prices are rather steep for what you get, most toppings cost extra and the food really isn't all that great.    I didn't have a single "ring" in any of my onion rings, only small, overcooked pieces (looked nothing like the pictures others have posted).  The staff seemed bothered to help anyone and simply rushed people through the line, even though it wasn't particularly busy.    The hotdogs were decent, but certainly nothing special.  I had a jumbo beef chili cheese dog and a pseudo-Chicago dog (everything but the sport peppers and poppy seed bun, because they don't offer them) myself.  I also tried the white and polish sausages that other family members were eating.  Truth be told, the sausages were the best of the bunch.    The chili was a generic beef-only sauce and the liquid cheese was very plain.  The french fries arrived dry and unsalted, but not particularly crispy.  They tasted "ok" once they were doctored up, but these aren't the type of fries you "crave" later.  The shakes are very expensive for the small size you get and the chocolate shake tasted just like powdered chocolate milk, which I found disappointing.  The Loganberry shake, however, was very good.    Unfortunately, for what you end up paying for a pair of hot dogs and a soda, I can go to much nicer eateries and have a higher quality meal that actually tastes great.  When it comes down to it, there are so many hot dog joints popping up all over the valley that it's quite easy to find somewhere better than Ted's.  The only thing they really have going for them is a recognizable name and a great location in the busy area of Tempe.    Unless you have no other choice, I recommend you save your money and get your hot dog fix somewhere else.

JI0fz2DMCSXgu-C2JhcqAQ.text: Best foot long hot dogs in the world!!!

YZK_tl7EuguA0F8REaIUJA.text: Great food, great service, just wish the line was shorter be ready to wait for an hour if you decide to go here

EKh1ExkCmXfK8CMyyGgsOQ.text: We stumbled upon this place on the way to another restaurant and I'm so glad we stopped. The shakes are creamy goodness!! The owner was grilling the dogs and each one has the crispy flame grilled taste. I got a white hot and all beef, both were fantastic. My Dad is from NY so it was too cool finding a place in Az that serves white hots. This is the perfect place if you're craving old school, made to order food.

R1ljiLpGvZyo4T6nwPXx5A.text: True New York taste! They have crispy delicious french fries and thin crispy onion rings. The Salens hotdogs that they use are very high quality and truly delicious! Best hot dogs that I've ever had! Also the Teds brand hot sauce deserves a special mention, its very tasty tangy and has just the right amount of spiciness to it and it's very complimentary to all of their menu items... A++++++ Teds!

2_agVj2jTOKD4tq0jDImrQ.text: Just the best hotdog ever!  Try a footlong or a white hot!  French fries with malt vinegar!  Wash it all down with an ice cold loganberry!

MfQp0XS26ReG1G0vg8n4VQ.text: Way overrated!!! They are using cheap weiners - NOT BEEF hotdogs. Weiners are just thrown on the grill and then into a hard bun. There is nothing spectacular about this place. You are better off buying Hebrew National and grilling it yourself. These are not coney dogs like Detroit Coney Grill down the street or James Coney Island hotdogs. Price is too expensive and the taste is awful - absolutely no flavor. You can't even taste the char because of the cheap weiner.

JxTI2OG4dIaTuGqO125chg.text: This was really disappointing, especially after the positive Yelp reviews.  The onion rings were made fresh. However, I've made better at home (and on my first and only try). The batter was bland and tasted "oily," if it had a flavor at all. The actual onion pieces were cut too small to have a good mouth-feel.  The charred beef jumbo hot dog I ate was okay. It was buried under a pleasant mountain of toppings--I asked for "everything"--and this was nice. The bun was typical; nothing that went above and beyond the Wal-Mart buns-in-a-bag experience.  I also had a jumbo burger. 1/3 pound. It was cooked okay; medium-rare in parts, medium in others. I suspect they were trying for medium. The toppings were acceptable and the bun was pretty good. The meat itself tasted unseasoned, but was fine.   We had a milkshake, too. Loganberry. Theoretically. It tasted like strawberry, and when I asked for confirmation that it was not strawberry, the staff offered to remake it. Okay, I thought this may be a gambit to save face--fine, let's let them remake the drink. I was told that they'd bring it out to us, so I sat down at the table. We were later "greeted" by an employee carrying our milkshake. She slammed it down on the table without comment (slopping some of it over the edge of the cup), and spun on her heel and returned to the service line.   All in all ... I really, really, really hope they had an "off night." We won't be going back, which is sad--all I wanted was a tasty hot dog served by folks who were friendly. I don't care that I'm being fleeced for a hot dog; I'll pay $4 for one if it is good and comes with quality service and preparation. If our evening is any indication, Ted's Hot Dogs has a long way to go with staff training and quality of sides. I appreciate that QSRs are hard things to staff well, but just hiring folks that are somewhat friendly and want customers to come back may be a good start.

_OYA2W2fh_DsxSKC0EFhfw.text: Our first visit here, we came because of the great reviews and weren't disappointed. They have great music, throwback atmosphere was enjoyable and service was prompt and friendly.   The burger was definitely better than your typical burger. It had a soft bun, and it was served nice and hot. You watch them make your burger and choose toppings as you go. The horseradish mustard was a definite plus!   Toppings were fresh. Bacon was cooked perfectly.   Fries were good-shoe string style. Onion ring style isn't what we prefer but many enjoy the crumbly coating type - we prefer beer battered.   Worth a visit if you're in the area.

sIlEglsUBpM4M2hUwPKxvA.text: Great place to have a Buffalo NY style hot dog. I love this place and it is close to work. Fun atmosphere with old timey music playing inside. You will often see Spiro (now deceased) who is the descendant of the famous Ted in there talking with a bunch of typical regulars.  I usually get a couple of the All Beef Jumbo Dogs flown in from NY with whatever I want on them with a side of melted cheese and some pickle spears. The chili is pretty good also. You can pick from a large array of items to put on your wiener or burger. They cook it right in front of you while you wait. You can smell the tasty aroma of the mesquite charcoal in the parking lot before you enter. Onion rings made from scratch. They have footlongs, brats, polish, white hots (which I call bockwurst) and more. Some of them made here locally at one of my favorite sausage places in central Phoenix. They also have tasty hamburgers and chicken along with homemade ice cream shakes.   Gets really busy with a long line during peak lunch hours. Get there before 11am or after 1pm. Poke me with a fork I'm done!

It's a hot dog..no science in cooking required. Still pricey for it about 10 bucks for a hot dog no drink no fries.

Kx8SHQL-9b0OH9H2IiDHdA.text: Anyone who's spent much time in Western New York, Buffalo in particular, knows about Ted's. And they know that it has a terrific reputation for being a go-to place for hot dogs. Now, I know what you are saying: Hot dogs, really? Yes, really. They are grilled over charcoal here. And the meat is a local Buffalo-area product which the locals there love. You have your choice of toppings, including pickle (sort of a Ted's thing). In addition, the onion rings are popular. Many years ago, I set a "personal best" when I ate two foot-longs at one sitting. I was fine afterwards, but probably not the best thing to do. There are burgers and other options, but the hot dogs (as the name implies) is the reason to go to Ted's. And if you are in Buffalo, check it out there. To my knowledge, this is the only one outside New York State. There's just one grilling line here, so on a busy day, it might take a few minutes to order and get your food. Added bonus: It won't cost much!

qTQQNW_JwE-KsHDflutU4w.text: How have I not reviewed this before? I've been coming here for at least 10 years now and we recently came back now that they have finished the renovation. Honestly, it's not all that different, cleaner walls and new video menu boards but the food is still excellent.  The best thing about Ted's is that they grill the hotdogs. This gives them a better flavor than your typical boiled dog. And they have lots of toppings, including mac and cheese, which turns out to be delicious. They also have excellent onion rings and fries, and you can get an order of "frings" which is a combination of both and more than enough for two people.  Here's the tip for customers, start looking at the menu when you get in line because the workers won't wait for you to get to the counter, they're looking for you to yell your order while in line so they can get it started. However, a tip for the restaurant is; once you get an order figure out a way to pass it down the line so that people don't have to repeat themselves. This last time that we were there my wife ordered chili cheese fries and no less than four people on the line asked her if she wanted the chili on top or on the side. Figure it out people! Maybe drive over to The Chuckbox and see how they use toothpicks in a code to let the other employees know what customers have ordered.  But overall, Ted's is a great place for people, like me, who like hot dogs!

JlUHD72Mq-dduzNcCWQTcQ.text: Will NOT be back! Highly overrated and overpriced for a simple hotdog. absolutely nothing special about this place. Ordered onion rings, was expecting onion rings but received a pile of bits and pieces of nasty. Very disappointing.

thZ3wrTJP8i_Hulk3UWL4w.text: This place is always busy. I can't recall a time when there wasn't a line to order food. The line goes pretty fast though so no biggie. It's a very popular spot but they have plenty of dining spaces inside and outside. They have redecorated the interior and the place doesn't look like a derelict diner anymore. It now looks brighter and more modern. The hotdogs are very tasty and they have a bunch of toppings from which you can choose. My picky husband always get hotdogs topped with chili and he loves it! As good as the hotdogs are, I come here for the onion rings. One of the best onion rings I've had. Thinly sliced onions, battered, and fried to crisp perfection. We'll be back for sure.

WlnyrbonphNbWwFyhAXJLg.text: Awesome place. Great hotdogs and burgers. The loganberry shake is really good. They can get really busy but the lines usually moves pretty quickly.

BYs0aMiJKb1zt19nz8sx9g.text: I love Ted's! Just ask for your dog extra done if you like it charred and charcoal-y like I do. I love their hot relish, and if you ask for "everything," you'll get everything BUT ketchup: just the way it should be.  Their chili is delicious! Tip: if you ask for the chili or cheese on the side, you get more for the same price. They do offer Udi's gluten-free buns now, which is awesome, but I've gotten in the habit of just asking for no bun and using a knife and fork...basically, you can't go wrong eating a Ted's dog.

EHxf_WC662dQEWg6ZOHImw.text: Had Ted's for dinner this evening. Flew back from Minnesota this afternoon and wanted a hot dog real bad. I had a foot long with chili, mustard and onions. The lady had polish with peppers and mustard. Small fries and a milkshake. Wow. Excellent choice, everything is made to order,great service. Will be coming back more often.

39QkZ00SatpfkB_7oJflmA.text: Been coming here for 15 years. Always loved them. Last few times have been so so. Still has good service.  They have expanded their menu which I jhave not tried their new items.   Brats were a little tougher and buns soggy my last visits. Don't know why. Cooked more or high humidity. ..IDK.   Fries were average in the past but the last 2 tines they're not hot. I couldn't eat em.   Overall a good change of pace but just not as good as I thought it was.

z1A4FP0ISiN0K8BM-QRRwg.text: Simply the best dog in the East Valley.   I've been frequenting Ted's since for many years and the quality has never changed. Open flame grill- the food cooks as you order. The all-beef dogs are amazing- and imported from New York, where the restaurant originated. There are other options such as white hots, hamburgers, foot longs, and brats. The french fries are good the onion rings are great. Ted's serves Pepsi products and accepts cash or credit card. The prices are very reasonable. The interior is decked in sports fare- and there's decent patio space available for outdoor dining (perfect during Spring weather). Expect crowds, especially around lunch time on weekends! Lots of out-of-state visitors here, and many spring training baseball fans (relatively close to Diablo stadium where the Angels play).   If you're in the mood for a locally legend hot dog, cooked to perfection then head on over to Ted's Dogs. You will not be disappointed.

uim4ukLa1bURD08sv-0yrQ.text: Very good charcoal grilled dogs. I'm not normally a hot dog kind of person, but Ted's is different!   I got the chillie and cheese dog and I was very satisfied.  I also like how they make the dogs in front of you. They ask what you want again as soon as the dog is cooked so no messing up your order.  Ted's is definitely my first choice for a good hot dog. I have yet to try their mac n cheese dog!

XwX3BjF6hT5mwFCvL5SsDQ.text: This was the most awkward ordering experience I have ever had. We stood at the counter with 4 employees looking away and talking to each other until we were asked what we wanted. Upon asking for a cheeseburger, the guy who asked just walked away. He came back and we asked for another burger, gone again. So I asked someone else if we could have fries as well. The woman never responded just started talking to a guy next to her and put the fries in the oil. We stood at the counter being completely ignored while everything cooked. I realize this is how things are done when it's busy, but we were the only ones. The woman who made the fries finally gave us our total, and when we tried handing her payment she was too caught up in her conversation again to notice. We sat for another couple of minutes just trying to pay. This is a ridiculous way to treat customers, I felt like I was bothering them by coming in. On top of that the food was terrible. This will be our last time coming here.

hKu1BBgx3ACeycMkx4mJnw.text: Your hotdog might take a bit, and it's nothing you can't do yourself on a grill, but this place is a cut above the rest in the hotdog arena. Not too expensive and you can pick all your options like subway or chipotle. A solid choice for a sub $5 quick bite.

Anyway, for the price of my vegetarian processed tofu on a plain, grocery-store bun, I was expecting a bit more punch.  But what I got was something that I could've heated up in the microwave at home.  No flavor :-(  No punch.

Fa12kB6tVudRvI_H0CZsDA.text: How awesome is this place!? I don't even like hot dogs, but I love getting them from Ted's! Have had foot longs, all beef, white hot.... Its all delicious. My daughter always gets the kids skinny dog with cheese sauce, and I love the onion rings!  I go out of my way to visit Ted's.

My husband loves the chili with cheese.  I recommend the all beef.  The employees make the place.  Everyone is friendly and efficient.  Yvonne is a hoot to chat with. Fun for a quick lunch.

jydKSe_Wosl6GAFaWNsLbQ.text: Best onion rings in town (hand battered and fried to perfection) and arguably the best hot dog(grilled on real coals not boiled) in town.  It is also the only place in town I know of to get a Loganberry shake.  This place has never let me down.

S5Ly7h_KA2BJpB1nrSUcTA.text: Damn this place is fantastic. It's another great Tempe example of a short order, Charcoal grilled fast food joint. The sausages our particularly fantastic while the hamburgers are actually pretty mediocre.  What really sets this place apart is the onion rings. I call them onion rings but that is really not doing them justice. It is more like taking a handful of chopped onions and dunking them in batter before dropping them in hot oil. So good.  I've not had one but my friend I've gone with says the milkshakes are fantastic as well

DcbrmWCcd44hZ_-Yl8tZLQ.text: Good food, but the service was SOOOO slow. Don't go in here if you have a quick lunch break. They aren't fast enough for that!

YVsbBcZKseMIaMPJxZYudQ.text: Ted's has been around forever for two reasons. Great quality and fair price.  I coworker had posted photos earlier this year, spending hours in line to take her daughter to Pink's Hot Dogs in LA. I asked why wait in an insanely long line for Pink's, when she can get better product at Ted's. She'd never heard of Ted's, so I made it a mission to take her for lunch. It was a super hungry day for me - I had an Italian Sausage with a side of a regular dog. The coworker had a jumbo dog, and we shared onion rings. The onion rings were amazing. All onion rings should be Ted's onion rings! Thin sliced, crispy breading - clearly made fresh to order.  My Italian Sausage was perfectly seasoned and had just the right level of spice. Topped with deli mustard and cooked peppers and onions. I could not have asked for a more delicious lunch. In hindsight, I should have eaten the regular dog first. It was tasty. Incredibly enjoyable. But with the flavor of the Italian Sausage still on my tongue, it was a little on the boring side. Truly, nothing wrong with it at all - and had I reversed the order of consumption, I would have loved both equally. My fault, not Ted's! If I had to come up with a con, it would be the location. Nowhere close to my house or stomping grounds, and too far from my office to make it a regular stop. Tempe people are soooo lucky!

Y0QSlay_ySMBcVsQmSU6QA.text: According to my son..."great hotdogs, definitely eat There! If you don't, I feel sorry for you."

08-r0VkemADdLZWX5a-cKA.text: Come in looking for a classic hot dog experience and you won't be disappointed. They char-grill everything. Half a dozen hot dog options, plus sausages, chicken sandwiches, burgers, fish  sandwiches, fries, onion rings, shakes, etc. Great kids meal deals.

photos.caption: Photo of Ted's Hot Dogs - Tempe, AZ, United States

wjIo1fmwFUtpNB0fHR4xLA.text: Teds was what I expected to be and more. The food was great. Has that homemade burger flavor and taste to it that I expect at like a bbq. I remember trying the split. The notion rings were really good. Only thing that would make the experience even better if the line was not so long and the ordering process was not a process. Over all really good food for great price.

_p1I8SlmbEY2y7y96CzQKQ.text: Best hot dog I ever had...Char broiled with special chili sauce is outstanding. Milk shakes are the best and try the Loganberry for a nice alternative to sodas. I always pick up some Webers mustard when I run out...  Fast service (these guys know how to handle a long line at lunch) and friendly help.

Q4UriBNNC6pI_px7c6boww.text: Love this place.  When I get that craving for a good charcoal grilled dog or burger I come straight here. Just can't resist at times.   Plenty of hot dog choices Wide variety of topping options Fries and onion rings are made fresh with your order.   Don't think; just go.

SBtp-3EJhLo_av9Zyd9ZGQ.text: Ted's is legendary in the Tempe; and thankfully less than 2 miles from the Burger Guys house. And only another 2 miles from my favorite burger in the Valley, Detroit Coney Grill. I will say this... Ted's probably has the best hotdog in town. Try a jumbo all beef with bacon and mac and cheese on top! Ok enough of the hotdog talk, this is a Burger Guy review...  The Burger - 8.5 (out of 10) Ted's makes a damn fine basic burger. When I think of a good ol' fashion classic burger, I think of the burger at Ted's. Ted's uses a charbroiler and they cook the meat right there in front of you while you wait in line. Great flavor on the loose packed thin beef patty (almost definitely chuck). Great bun to meat to cheese to veggie ratio. The Burger Guy gets the double cheese with bacon. Side note: the french fries are good here, as well as basically everything else on the menu. I don't know what's going on with Tempe but there are some awesome burger places in this town.   Note: Score is for the burger only. Other factors such as service, price, and ambience are not considered.  Valley of the Sun Burger Tour  -Ted's Hotdogs 8.5 -Detroit Coney Grill 9

0AWl0OPLsJFc4k_rT0Mv2w.text: Eh, not so good... Mediocre food.  Honestly, I do not understand all the hype about this place.  I have had infinately better from a street stand.  Skimp on the condiments but their new dips are pretty good.  The fries and onion rings are lousy and service is slow.   Ted's is a disappointment.

ShuVukv7fJ1SlN5Kl5fggQ.text: Gah, I hate when a local institution like Ted's slides so far downhill that a bad review is warranted. Sometimes you should just leave well enough alone. This is not high cuisine, nor is it supposed to be. Ted's used to serve the real deal - great NY style dogs, brats, and kielbasa. The line went out the door, but they kept it moving. Now some kid with a iPad takes your order and on this Sunday afternoon I waited 10 minutes for a dog and a polish? And to top it off... both were cold. Looks like they spent a lot of money remodeling too. The old decor was just perfect - old pictures on the wall, wood paneling. Now it looks like some generic fast food concept you'd find in any mall food court.  Sorry, Ted's, but I think I just ate my last dog...

myOuxImc0TBh-VLWYsNyxg.text: Not bad at all. Hotdogs are really good and you can dress them up however you want. The bacon cheese was not great because the bacon was not cooked right. But the chili cheese dog was awesome.

_XrEDuZ4iuZCAbptUd951g.text: Best dogs west of the Mississippi!!  All beef chargrilled with their house made hot sauce.  Damn mouth is watering might have to go there and get 2 more.

photos.caption: Photo of Ted's Hot Dogs - Tempe, AZ, United States. That was lunch today... It&#39;s all in my belly now.

QIZWdIifWbhWAp90wXurvg.text: Great bratwursts and hot dogs. Customizable. Made right in front of you in line. Great atmosphere. Good casual first date spot or to bring with you on a picnic!

V6zf_6uy1F9Xewie_8rFmQ.text: After getting over the face that I'm pretty sure TED's hot dogs stole te TED talk typeface I walked in and order a couple corn dogs and there cheesy fries.   The service was really great. Very sweet man and woman running the front when I went through. Super sweet and nice. Nothing wrong with the service. The food tho was mediocre on a Natasha beddingfield day! Like I'm feeling generous. The corn dogs were no better than something you'd get at sonic. I could've eaten a couple of them. They aren't very big and aren't very special. There spicy dipping sauce is probably the best part about them. The fries, don't get them. Get the onion rings. The fires are so bad I wanted to die eating them. The onion rings aren't bad they're really light but they still taste better than the reheated fries.   All and all the place was eh, probably won't ever go back but I'm not super upset I went. It was fine for lunch with my coworkers and I liked my corn dogs. So yeah. Thanks TED but I like your talks better.

cv5ntlnsCsA9UOMgvQPCvQ.text: Not quite what we expected, especially for the prices. The milkshakes were excellent though.

Iq_Ncoqoxk64BfBjaXX1bw.text: Haven't been here in years and we finally decided to come here after church. Just in time right before lunch time rush! Service was quick and fast so the line moved quickly.  We got 2 regular hotdogs and 1 brat and 1 polish! And fries. I live the burnt hotdog/sausage skin... So yummy :) idk if my salt tolerance is going down but i thought that the brat got really salty towards the end... Still yummy tho..  Glad to eat at Ted's again!  Coke goes so well with hotdog and fries :)

rKGD6SGl5k82_lOjXWIlFw.text: I grew up eating those Seitz hot dogs that came in the silver package and on sale you could get 4 packs for a dollar or something like that.  They were awful, and I'm pretty sure if I get any chronic or terminal illnesses, it's going to be from eating about a thousand of those.  Then I lived in Orlando for a few years and became a regular at Hot Dog Heaven.  Now THIS is a hot dog!  Then I started paying more attention.  Well, on Saturday Mr. M and I were on a hot dog cruise and stood in the very long line at Ted's to order 2 jumbos with cheese & mustard, mine also with relish, a bottle of water, and a chocolate shake.  The total was $15.55 and reminded me that I really need to remember to carry our own water with us.  That would have saved 2 bucks.   Anyway, HEY, back to the dogs....chargrilled and perfect!  I was taken back to Hot Dog Heaven and we both thoroughly enjoyed our meal.  The milkshake was rich, chocolatey deliciousness too.  I will definitely get a craving for Ted's and can't wait to go back and try other items on the menu.

sBGElLe3WADAFKywzRwKTA.text: Ted's is a Phoenix original by way of Buffalo and has probably fed tens of thousands ASU students and teachers over the years.  Ted's history is similar to that of other Hot Dog pioneers like Paul and Betty Pink, Nathan Handwerker, and Dick Portillo. All who started with just a Hot Dog cart, and grew their business into something very special.   But Ted's is the immigrant story of Theodore Spiro Liaros, who came to the US from Greece at the turn of the last century.    One of these days, someone will take the time to write the history of all the hard working Greeks who came here with just the shirt on their back, to start a restaurant or food business.  But I digress, because you come to Ted's to enjoy the charcoal grilled hot dogs and hamburgers and all the friendly conversation on line. Ahh, and those charcoals are white hot (see photo), which makes their food oh so delicious.    They have Hot Dogs, Hamburgers, Brats, Italian Sausages, French Fries and home made beer batter like Onion Rings (photo), along with Milk Shakes and Malts.  Ted's is really just great food, served simply. I can highly recommend those afore mentioned All Beef Hot Dogs, Sausage and Onion Rings. All the tube steaks are $3.79 and you can take home some of their special bottled mustard for $5.39 as I did.  Enjoy!

photos.caption: Photo of Ted's Hot Dogs - Tempe, AZ, United States. Flaky and tasty onion rings

v6gWHcQ-iUB1GahNPE6Lxg.text: I have come here since I was a kid and my wife and I eat here once or twice a month now.  It's packed every day for lunch and the evenings seem to attract more families for dinner.  The hot dogs or hamburgers are grilled in front of you and the staff is friendly and operates well behind the counter.  The restaurant is consistently spotless and everyone is very attentive to what you may need.  At the busiest times the seating space seems limited and you might need to take the food home.  Their milk shakes, fries, and onion rings are also really good though the fries seem to get soggy after they cool down so eat them quickly.  In all the times I've eaten here I have never had a bad meal, they have all been good.

UwGPsCW75kMQr7w5gQZmFQ.text: I really can't believe people love this place. The service is good. But the food is so bland. I had a foot long chilli cheese dog...blech.

McNgC0YcMCcSAKcAEHm33Q.text: Here now for the first time. Having watched a food channel special on hot dogs I needed a fix. I ordered the bratwurst( w/kraut & spicy mustard) & chili and cheese(w/onions). Both were spot on and had that charcoal grilled flavor that I like. I also got an order of onion rings to make sure I over ate....again. The Oring order was big enough to share. The line was pretty big mostly held up by tourists that were so amazed by the grilled dog process that they couldn't move or speak. I would not hesitate to return. bmpKB5zq4lnL1_aSnZJ4bw.text: Unique longstanding dependable and worth a visit. Glad to have enjoyed their unique custom made hot dogs. Plenty of condiments and the prices well they are higher than the K but that is OKAY because the place is rocking indeed.

1xvhPICtW9UvjuMGEiHr0w.text: This is the only Ted's location outside of NY, so my friend was super excited to try it out. I added mac and cheese to my dog and that made it so delicious. The onion rings were crunchy and flavorful. I would definitely come back here again. 0UZtA4P55geeP1uzajpjaw.text: Hadn't been here in about two years and remembered that it was good so we went back. The place has gone downhill. They used to staff the place appropriately to keep the line moving but now it's excruciatingly slow. Ordered a Chicago style, asked if they knew how to make it and they said yes. They did not. When they said it was hot sauce I asked why they put hot sauce on my hot dog and they just stared blankly. Husbands burger resembled a tiny hockey puck.
