The employees are courteous and the service is great.  It's amazing that the cook can remember all the orders he takes at one time without messing them up.  I would recommend to come before noon or between 1pm and 3pm on weekdays, or you will be waiting in a very long line.  Regardless, I would definitely recommend this to anyone looking for a good hot dog or hamburger.

8EgnPhYzvsQi3kC3okOM4Q.text: Teds is the best place in town to go get a hot dog! It is cooked and prepared right in front of you, and the burgers are just as good.

280dyg7OMXEZndRXRc3rHQ.text: This place is the best hot dog joint around.  They have a large selection of dogs to choose from and they are all cooked over a wood burning grill.  I always leave satisfied.  You order and then stand around as the dog cooks, waiting until it's done to give your condiment order.  I could go without that part because people are just piled up and it makes it go a lot slower since you can't put an order in because 10 people in front of you are just standing waiting for their dogs to cook.  I think they should take the order, cash out, and then get the food cooked and delivered.  That is the only reason I removed a star.    However, I'll stand around for a hot dog that good.  Sometimes they are too busy for me to wait around so I will do a drive-by but I usually stick to their less busy hours.    The one other thing that has always irked me was how badly they assault that poor defenseless dog.  They cut that thing, and slice it as if it just insulted their mother.  Apparently it helps because it is delicious.  I just wish it didn't have to take such abuse prior to arriving in my mouth.  I am a big proponent of humane treatment, even after it has taken its form as food.

cI87OLroXThQcSwE1SZZbA.text: I have wanted to eat here for some time and finally did so today. It was a long but fast moving line of those with sausages ordering to eat the same. If you a young lady on the prowl this is the place for you. The all beef dog was perfect!!!! The cheese fries were yummy.  All for less than seven bucks. A great lunch. I plan on going back on Monday for a brat.

JRKEPD6VHod4rS957oPaSg.text: You like hotdogs?  Motor (thats me) says get in your Mommy's oldsmobuick and get over to TEDS!  AND you sissys that like "sonoran" style dogs talking smack about Teds, go back to Tucson and eat your fru fru pineapple topped dogs with peanut butter.   This is old style, 4th of July chargrilled hotdogs and hamburgers.  Makes my mouth water.  Ok so visualize and taste this in your mind.  First the juicy hamburgers that have the hardwood charcoal taste that makes your mouth water.  The crispy ice berg lettuce, juicy tomato and onion make this a purist burger lover's dream.  Real good home made taste.   So now act you like you always do on the 4th of July and get an all beef hotdog.  First a warning.  You will crave their hotdogs after you eat em.  The crispy plump skin that cracks in your mouth and the taste is like when you were a kid and watching the fire works on the fourth.  Add the spicy brown mustard with their ketchup "hot sauce" and buddy you got yourself dilemma.  The dilemma you ask? Is do you order one more hotdog cause they are soooo goood!  Try the Italian for a spicy dog.  Don't start with me on the fries and onion rings.  Just make sure you wear your fat pants.  Motor out and going back for another dog.

1cAHg6LPalV8gVYMYU7Q9Q.text: A friend and I went to Teds Hot Dogs on a Friday evening, it was both of ours 1st time there and we were not disappointed. We too have to say Ted's Hot Dogs are among the best in the valley and how lucky are we to have Ted's out of his 7 locations, mostly being in the New York area, we have one in Tempe AZ!  Once you walk in you see where the line is forming, don't be alarmed, it's really not a slow moving line, once in line you place your order you can c watch your dog (or burger, but really who goes to a HOT DOG joint to order a burger?) cooking on a grill, getting plump and nice grill marks on them! Then once it is cooked, you will be asked what you want on it, now the chili cheese dog did look great but I went for an all-beef hot dog with mayo (that's how I like it) sliced pickles, grilled onions & peppers! BOY O BOY was it good!!  My friend ordered the foot long dog with chili. We also got some french fries & their freshly handmade onion rings, which were very good. They have other types of dogs on the overhead menu, brats, polish, white?, and reg dogs and the foot long & all beef.  Next time I will try the polish dog!

gAJ7Xx8O0tG73oAJ9D1sFw.text: Awesome.  Good all beef dogs/brauts/polish sausage, good toppings, awesome fries, good shakes, pretty good stuff.  They also make their own hot sauce.  Only complaint: Store bought hot dog   buns - they don't try to hide it or anything, but seeing the bag of Rainbow, or Aunt Haddys, or whatever it was, just kills it a little bit.   Homemade buns  would be cool, but this place is pretty great. I like the  dining area as well. Just simple, bright, and clean.

sTCsRuLhRLugQ4ZAR-hiFA.text: I've visited a friend in the Phoenix area twice and both times we went to Ted's. The first visit was at his suggestion but the second time around, I pretty much demanded it. The line was pretty long each time, but for good reason...great food. REALLY like the charbroil aspect; I had a hot dog the first visit and a brat the second - both were worth writing home about. poawVPpAF9SlvkcT5X58tg.text: Two words: Loganberry Shake. That is the key to maximum enjoyment of your Ted's experience.  The hot dogs are good and perfectly burnt (you can of course order them other levels of done if you're a huge weirdo), the specialty sausages are amazing (try a white hot), and the fries are these cute not-quite-full-size cuts that are the ideal balance between crispy outside and mushy inside. T7gD8nWdjzhoj_P0FZ89vA.text: Five stars for the awesome dogs. I get the jumbo with mustard and onions and always enjoy it. Good hot dogs are hard to find. UPDATE: Tried the onion rings today - they are great except for one thing - they should be sliced thicker. They are battered, not breaded, the way rings should be. Huge order.

f1ljnxGlsWWoIZ-qIKcTUw.text: I friggin' love hot dogs, and this place does NOT disappoint!  If you've ever been there you know there's probably going to be a long line when you arrive.. but you wait anyway because it's Ted's Hot Dogs and it's delicious! The line goes fast, and before you know you it you are up there placing your own order.  The menu is pretty simple: Hot dogs  But there's a variety of different kinds, ranging from your basic doggy, to delicious savory bratwurst, and various delicious sausage treats in between. They cook it right in front of you, as you direct the condiment distribution... my mouth is usually watering throughout this entire process.  I have never had a bad experience with Ted's, and although some people complain about the line I have never had it take more than 5-10 minutes to get through... and it's well worth it!

BzRfVn2jgvoBWz3LwX-S9A.text: I love reading about my yelp friends' vacation finds. I always bookmark them because although I never know when I'll be in that part of the country, I do know those bookmarks will eventually become tourist destinations for me. My yelp bud Tim S. knows his comfort foods. When he raves about a pizza in New York, a cheesesteak in Philly, or a hot dog in Phoenix, I'm so there. Wait a Hot Dog in Phoenix? That can't be right. This ain't Chicago or New York. Or is it? Ted's is a Buffalo, NY Hot Dog blooming right here in the middle of the desert, transplanted in 1983 from it's 1927 original wintery environment. Sometimes when you are a food tourist, it's ok to over order and try a few different things. It's not ok for your waistline, but "Hey you're on vacation!" At least that's what I tell myself. And I got absolutely no judgement from Ted's when I ordered a Regular Hot Dog, a Jumbo All Beef dog, an Italian Sausage, and a Bratwurst. Chased down with some Onion Rings and a Loganberry Milkshake. So what makes Ted's so good, is the charcoal. As I came in, they were adding a bunch of new charcoal to the grill. It gives the dog a nice smokey flavor and a good snap. Each of my 4 dogs/ sausages were excellent and it's tough to choose which one was best. I actually think I preferred the basic hot dog, because of the soft grind of the wiener offset with the crunchy slightly charred casing. It was texture heaven for sure, and I got this one dressed in classic Chicago style - chopped onions, relish, tomato, pickle, and yellow mustard. I dressed the all beef with kraut and chopped onions - excellent dog although a little firmer in texture, as most beef dogs are. They have polish, bratwurst, italian, and a white hot under their sausage menu. I read a couple of slightly negative reviews on the white hot, so while it sounded very interesting, I had no room to put one down on this visit. Italian and Bratwurst it was for me and I got them dressed the same way with grilled onions and peppers. I opted for the hot sauce on the side. The hot sauce pairs perfectly with the Italian Sausage. This is a nice and spicy Italian. Adding the hot sauce seemed to just reinforce that same flavor, rather than cover it up. Ted's has an interesting home made hot sauce. If you made a salsa out of hot dog condiments, this is what you would get - relish, onions, in a ketchup vinegar base. For the bratwurst I went straight up with some brown deli mustard. Awesome! Next visit, I'm trying a chili cheese dog for sure. The onion rings taste like an onion loaf, but not super peppery. They have a great batter here, but I like that you can still taste the onion and there isn't too much batter. The Loganberry shake is a must order. The perfect sweet creamy drink to offset the spicy Italian Sausage. From what I understand loganberry is a Western NY flavor, because you don't see it around these here parts too much. It's like a red blackberry. I have no idea if it was loganberry flavored ice cream or vanilla ice cream with loganberry syrup. Whatever it is, order it and you will be happy. I can't wait until the next time I'm in Phoenix (or Buffalo) to get me a charcoal grilled dog at Ted's. yelp.com/biz_photos/teds...

photos.caption: Photo of Ted's Hot Dogs - Tempe, AZ, United States. Bratwurst, Italian Sausage, All Beef Jumbo Dog with kraut and onions, regular dog Chicago style, onion rings,  loganberry shake.

N-b6BI3W1UrfF6ri8ckyMQ.text: You can't beat hamburgers and hotdogs cooked on a charcoal grill!  I would have given it 5 stars if only they had fresh ground beef patties instead of frozen, but it was still delicious! Can't wait to go back and try a hotdog next time!

Q5FE-B-_BZ4ZyuDv1zDnzA.text: Wow, it's been years since I have been here. Decided to go all out and get a chili cheese dog and cheese fries. I had forgotten about how delicious these dogs are!

6K9ArGDiMvBqeBk4uiDu1g.text: Ted's is always awesome for a quick bite. They might have a line out the door but they're super efficient, fast and friendly. The food is always to die for: fresh and hot. If it looks like there's a ton of people in there, don't be discouraged. The line moves faster than you'll ever realize and they take your order way before you're near the counter. It's not the same person preparing all of your food so its all getting done at the same time and you don't have to wait. They have a drink person, a grill person, a fry person, a shake person... As long as you're okay with the Buffalo Bills pennants around the place (haha), you'll really enjoy your meal and experience here.

DXHNEYHd8aYh83402v2JjQ.text: I love this place!!!! The hot dog was great, but my favorite thing was definitely the onion rings!!! Their creamsicle shake was also really good :)

photos.caption: Photo of Ted's Hot Dogs - Tempe, AZ, United States

VyqSXN230tWEvsFnZT_E4A.text: My mistake going here for lunch. Ordered doublebacon cheese burger w/ onion ring and a regular dog. You know, from their hall of flame menu board. They acted as if they had never heard of it before, and made it to their order not mine.  Crew so big of hurry they did not put bacon or onion ring on burger. Lettuce was pulled soaking wet from bin and put on burger making bun a soaking wet mess. Burger came up before the people ahead of me. It sat there incomplete and soaking wet. Then they forgot the regular hot dog. Charged me for everything including onion rings i didn't order. Hot dog bun was ICE cold. Burger bun a wet mess and w/o bacon. I got refund for onion rings i did not order and they put a cold onion ring on my slop burger. Ordered and paid for but did not get what i ordered. Strange they had plenty of time to bullshit with ASU sports idiots. But not enough time to get customers order right. I drove 56 miles round trip and got screwed out of money and a decent hot meal.

5uiej_x36cDz0WMarQRrpg.text: You want a really good hot dog and onion rings? THIS IS YOUR PLACE! The service is awesome (they treat you like family) and honestly I don't care for onion rings but theirs is to die for. Do yourself a favor and just go there, it's worth it!

PHFydj7GNlIF5IQ2erkOxw.text: A hot dog, is a hot dog. Unless it's Ted's.   Seriously there is black magic going on here. Apparently they start by getting a super high quality dog made for them back in Buffalo, then they beat the heck out of it above open flame! Seriously they poke and slice the dog up while it's being grilled over white oak charcoal and it picks up all that smokey goodness while cooking.   There are two other shining stars at Teds. Their house hot sauce and the Loganberry drink. The loganberry is basically glorified koolaid, but man is it good. The hot sauce is more of a relish and is unlike any other I have had. I'm not really sure what's going on in it, but it's just a little spicy, sweet and awesome.  Their cheese is straight up east coast style cheese sauce. Basically cheese wiz. If you like that sort of thing go for it. The chili is that midwest no beans kind. Not my thing, but that's fine. I always get the jumbo all beef topped with mustard, relish, onions and the hot sauce.   Everything not fried is cooked over that same white oak charcoal, so it all picks up that goodness. That means if you're not feeling a hotdog, everything else is going to be sold, but keep in mind "Hot Dog" is in the name of the place. Don't expect for their burger to change your world.  Last time I checked their were 8 locations. 7 in Buffalo, NY and this one.

WjH3TSODMJm6RG9Cy91iaw.text: First time trying teds. Only issue is no prices and no combos. So got burger with cheese which was really good. Will be back to try other things.

5s5RpQjmsa58-3lZrXDJiQ.text: Went there on a Sunday 3 weeks ago to get hot dogs . I have come to expect a long slow line to order my food, usually 10 to 15 minutes, it irritates me , but I tolerate it.  On this day I waited  at least 35 minutes to order a couple hot dogs, that's not just poor service, that's complete total Disrespect by management toward their customers. As I got near front of line, I did see the manager poke his head out from the back of the restaurant , so I know the manager working that day. He didn't seem to concerned about the wait time, no sense of urgency. By the time  I got to the front of line I forgot to order the soda my wife wanted, because I was so completely pissed off about standing in line so long. I ordered a White Hot as usual, wife got a regular hot dog, the food was fine.  I understand they remodeled this place a couple years ago, what a wasted opportunity to re-design the ordering process. You know I can go to the Dutch Brothers over on Mill & Southern and they almost always has a line that snakes thru the parking lot.  Yet it only takes few minutes to get thru the line at Dutch bros because there is someone walking car to car taking orders with a smart phone device. You know Ted's, it wouldn't be that difficult have an employee with an I-pad  taking orders in line, and maybe add a second toppings station, and another register to facilitate the ordering  process . A 35 - 40  minute wait, or even 10-15 minute wait, is too long of a wait to order a Hot dog, it speaks volumes about how little you care about your customers.

B2CNDPFMpjAnhC4V8EA_AA.text: Delish.  In the midst of my break (okay, lapse) from vegetarianism, I sought out this place for meaty delights.  When I want meat, I don't look for a steak--I want burgers and dogs, and Ted's did not disappoint.  With many dogs, the primary taste is from whatever condiments you put on the wiener.  With Ted's dogs, you get a smoky, slightly burnt taste of a REAL charcoal grilled frank that is enhanced by your custom toppings.  My tastes are simple and easy to please.  I like a foot long with just extra deli mustard--don't need more than that.  My wife likes more--mustard, ketchup, a little relish, and pickles.  Doesn't matter how you want it--Ted's will serve it up awesome.  Add fries and you've got a full meal for cheap.  Forget Circle K, and Wienerschnitzel can bite me.  Ted's has the dogz you're looking for.

UO7X6PpC8tBuJwPfDXFa3g.text: Whenever I stop by for lunch, there's always a line.  And you know what long lines mean: delicious, fresh food.  If the line is long (so, closer to the main door), the wait can be about 15-20 minutes, and plenty of time to change your mind from wanting a Brat, or maybe an Italian sounds better, or maybe the White Hot, nah I think I'll try a Sea Dog, or Polish?  No, Italian, yes, an Italian with fries and onion rings?  Just onion rings.  I'm indecisive, if you couldn't tell.  Their most recent addition has been to add mac and cheese on your freshly grilled, and perfectly burnt (in a good way!) hot dog, for an extra 75 cents.  This and chilli, is the most amazing thing ever.  And don't forget to get some cheese on the side!  I might have to start attending cheese-aholic meetings, for the sake of my cholesterol (no, I refuse to see exercise as an option here).  Cut to the chase:  My favorite things about this place, the perfectly grilled hot dogs, great choice of toppings (only the cheese, mac and cheese, and chilli are an extra charge), and those Teddy Bars look so good!  Though I've yet to try one.  My only complaint is the wait, but I've noticed that Ted's isn't so busy at dinner.  I hope I didn't just jinx that

InLyrzU6HWRb8BBAkrHwlw.text: Went here for the first time yesterday. Wife and I were starving and couldn't decide so we ended up trying a regular dog, a brat, a white hot, and a cheese burger between us. Oh my god. They were all so good. The range of toppings was awesome, we felt like kids in a candy store. Rounded it out with a flight of sauces for the perfectly cooked fries. So good I'm getting emotional.

syIRwg5JDxH6o6Iz4pSCIQ.text: They have a great selection of toppings for any size burger or dog. Great grilled flavor. They finally started accepting credit cards too!

oMZh9Cfo7l-JDJuxV3c_xA.text: My experience was just "ok."  The hot dog was cooked well but wasn't anything special. I was excited when I saw the onion rings but was let down by the taste. The ordering process was a little confusing because the line was formed to the left where I couldn't see the menu. Then after I had already paid they had to call me back up to clarify my order (they did this for all 5 orders around mine).  Overall it not a bad experience but it was a little disappointing as I have been meaning to try this place for years.

I8tkrtDYun2z0Fx0OAn1xQ.text: My first visit to Ted's. Went with a native of buffalo so was schooled on what to order and how to get the dog dressed.  Had the original footlong loaded with double hot sauce and it was the bomb. The homemade onion rings hit the spot too. I will definitely do this again and again and again.  I cant even imagine life without a visit to Ted's now.

photos.caption: Photo of Ted's Hot Dogs - Tempe, AZ, United States. First Timer. Went a little nuts with the rings and the fries. Finished them both

op9pH7yhgTbnoVrxjd3D2A.text: Love me some teds hot dogs! Been going here since high school and it's a sure thing for good hamburgers and hot dogs. They recently remodeled and made a few upgrades to the menu. Creepy grill guy with the mustache has worked there for over 20 years lol.

57JUulpe3DnPC6XkCeQA6A.text: What do you call a hot dog race?... Wiener takes all!  And so does Ted's Red Hots!  You really can't argue with their history.  They have been making hot dogs and sausages since the 20's in Buffalo, NY.  By some grace of god the made their way to Arizona and the rest is history.  This place must be on your AZ Favorite Food place.  Depending  upon what time you arrive you may have to endure standing in line in front of their grill where you will have to smell all the smells and simply salivate until you get your own.  No matter your meat choice, you will not be disappointed.    PRO TIP:  Ask for a toasted bun, and you must try the hot sauce!

pBkla7EbtgmGXTQo-mdqUQ.text: Definitely delicious and an experience I always look forward to.  The hardest part is choosing what to order because everything is good and I want it all.  I prefer the all beef hot dogs and usually order one and pair it with another style (braut, polish, or red hot).  Their burgers are delicious and the perfect size.  Onion rings are homemade and made to orders.  Pro tip: Although I am a purest and don't usually enjoy ketchup on my hot dogs, order the Ted's red hot sauce.  It is ketchup based yet extremely tasty. Also, the grilled onions and peppers are a side condiment option that most people miss.

XjDA11xHduQwt8Fb3DDCJg.text: What a great taste of Buffalo I n Tempe.  From the second you walk in the smell of charbroiled hotdogs and onion rings as only Teds can do. It really is like being back in Buffalo,NY. Just fantastic

V6A9FywqtvA-UqFXJnypqA.text: I had a chicken sandwich and it was precooked and it tasted like card board.  Do not order chicken sandwich.  Needless to say. I'm not coming back.

2b6eiD5M8PJFKUxneijhsw.text: I drive from East Mesa to eat hot dogs at Ted's. They cook them over charcoal, so you get the picnic feel. They have many varieties, also burgers, etc. I love Ted's!

xT5IxDinov9G-npFPZfqwQ.text: Such a cool spot! Onion rings are amazing. Bratwurst with onions peppers and sauerkraut was nostalgically perfect and delicious. Loved the ambiance, service and company history. Thumbs up!!

photos.caption: Photo of Ted's Hot Dogs - Tempe, AZ, United States. Perfect casual date night for fun couples!

YCHIYR-mHYTO51VzUaVB0w.text: Always a wonderful experience. The dogs and brats are first rate. They put what you want on it. Super tasty. We always get some rings and a shake. Can't go wrong.   The place is very clean and lots of parking.

rwRPOjFx07mo9lrMi0Erpw.text: Recently moved into the area.  We'd heard mixed reviews about this hotdog joint so we weren't in a hurry to try it.  Finally decided to stop in.  OMG the burgers and dogs smell amazing being cooked over that charcoal grill.  Fresh multiple toppings and generously applied just the way you like is awesome.  We are sold, Teds is terrific, we love it and have become regulars!

amIktv55An2VN30le6Gchw.text: Don't waste your time. Literally drove 30 minutes cause I heard great reviews & came for customer appreciation day. 91 cents a hot dog. The hot dogs taste like backyard grilled hot dogs, you literally can make them yourself. They also burnt some of the hot dogs.  The fries are okay.  In my opinion Costco has a better deal & they taste better.

0pErYCPzbjUDASuXKaHX1g.text: When I say I can't remember the last time I ate at Ted's I mean it! I know I've eaten here in the past (like...many, MANY years ago) but I don't remember it all. Even when I walked in nothing rang a bell. Anyway...  I was in the area and randomly stopped in with my mom and sister. I'm not a big hot dog eater and was planning on getting something else when I walked in, but 1) I had a big lunch earlier and wasn't really starving so just a regular hot dog sounded like it would hit the spot and 2) the dogs are grilled right in front of you to order. I'll eat them, but I'm not a big fan of boiled hot dogs, so when I saw the grill it sounded more appealing.   Like I said I got a regular hot dog w/mustard, BBQ sauce and jalapenos. I like the topping bar and the many different things you can choose. Honestly, you can put anything you want on them. There's a list of toppings on the menu, but if there's something else you want and they have it, they'll throw it on your hot dog. A woman in front of me wanted red onion on hers (I'm guessing they have them for burgers) so they got them out and added it to hers.   Also got cheese fries. The cheese was yummy! My mom got potato salad with her hot dog. I tried it and it was fine, but nothing special.   I also had a vanilla malt that was delicious. I LOVE it when places do malts and not just milkshakes.  When we came in we were lucky. There was only a few people in front of us so the wait wasn't that bad (remember, everything is made to order). However, when we sat down a line started to form and I can imagine the wait can get backed up.

IN8PGHKzsaPPC6HyZ81JlA.text: Went to Ted's for national hotdog day and was pleasantly surprised. $.92 for a regular dog!! All though the wait was very long (to be expected for this event) but the quality of the food was great for how busy the place was. Every worker there was very friendly and helpful despite the sheer mass of people in the establishment. I would highly recommend Ted's to anyone looking for a good dog or burger even on days other than national hotdog day!

F3AGoMdIwxTNWE-rCNQ9ng.text: Why are you cheapening your food? You get plenty of business, stop it! Your customers have been loyal and faithful. Return the favor!

Z9j2hSKewAwKFu0iEOHhBg.text: We visited Ted's in WNY and were very glad we found one close by, PROBLEM, our order was wrong but because they were busy we didn't wish to make a fuss about it. We might go back for a second chance

tdXUP09CtQgA7eDvWot99Q.text: Ted's has the best white hots around especially when they are char grilled well.  Add cheese and it makes it even better.  Add the stringy onion rings and it is perfection.  Fries and onion ring portions are enough for two.  Love this place and look forward to their next location.

m94Mzy76MkXYXMF2Q2Syzw.text: We continue to drive the 25 miles from our house to Ted's simply because they have the best hot dogs, brats, hamburgers, onion rings, and malts in the valley. They are simply wonderful!

AutItGMnn3TDcqvk1wCp-w.text: We have gone to Teds over the past few years.  We always order the Jumbo all beef hotdogs.  We went there today.. service was extremely  Slow.  Ordered 2 all beef jumbo hot dogs.  When we took them to Our table, we could not believe how small they were. We had Taken a photo on my from the last time we went to Teds. The all beef hotdog was much bigger.  I took my hot dog back to the Counter and asked 2. Employees if it was the jumbo size All beef hotdog.  They said yes.  I said "really." You can get a better JUMBO all beef hotdog at Costco or other grocery stores For a lot less.  We are Not going back.

DhjYVwEDCR2gnyTMOMhTXA.text: We ordered the footlong bacon and cheese, footlong chili and cheese, fries and a kids mac and cheese meal with the applesauce. Ted's grills the dogs in front of you and does it right with charcoal. Right when you get out of car, you can smell it in the air to when you walk through the front doors. The hot dogs were cooked just right and the fries were thin and crispy. My son enjoyed his mac n cheese and of course, ate the applesauce first. He loved playing with the hat he was given with his meal too.   The restaurant was well maintained and very clean, as well as the restroom. We will definitely be back to try some of the other dogs like the white hot and sausages.

YCIEt8j8rg3-5Hp2wSfwHA.text: This place is amazing. Have been coming here since I was a student at ASU 20 years ago. You really can't go wrong here because the quality of the meats are amazing. My go to is the chili cheese dog with fries and onion rings. I am not sure how they make the chili but it is ridiculous. Do yourself a favor today and go to Ted's.

ah3Hl7qJ9yQNguttBbmTqw.text: Just leaving Ted's. The food was meh. Specifically, the fries were almost cold and they had Coke products to drink. I prefer Pepsi products. The footlong dog was quite tasty. As for the seating, it was ridiculous. The booth seating was made for skinny people which I do not fall into that category. There is also a bar type seating at the window which would have worked had the customer order line of people not been blocking it. Then there was the cost. My order of a footlong dog, regular fries, and small drink cost me $11.20. I just paid it. Later I looked at my receipt and saw I was $1.50 over charged. They changed me for chili and cheese that was not on my dog.

7djoK-ftL_rI_AtU0Ge13Q.text: This place is amazing. The dogs are grilled fresh and made to order. I'll tell ya if you like hot dogs you'll love this place

photos.caption: Photo of Ted's Hot Dogs - Tempe, AZ, United States

H8UsaMfXC7WJAiHvRpWvcA.text: If you are looking for a good fresh cooked hot dog, or sausage, this is the place to go! They cook the meat while you are waiting in line, which I thought was pretty cool. It was actually kind of intimidating at first, if you don't know what to do. The sausage was good, although pleas note that 1 is more than enough! The fries and onion rings are good too!   If you're ever in the area and want a good hotdog or sausage, stop by Ted's!

DMPYFpGIznmKOCDdb0Laqg.text: Great place and honest cooking right in front of you.

h_8_qphL2WCUrvsdZBhvgg.text: I have been going to text for over 20 years. This is by far the best hotdog in town. No where else can you get them char broiled instead of boiled. Their shakes and malts are awesome also.

wLvu09v5WNa3OIJwbtpniA.text: Took the short 15 minute drive out to Broadway and McClintock today and ordered up an all-beef hot dog with chili, cheese and onions, and an Italian Sausage dog with mustard, ketchup and a pickle. Both dogs were near perfect.  Some nice char on both dogs providing a good crunch. The only suggestion would be to amp up their chili a little bit.  It's pretty bland, but is otherwise fine.  I meant to get a side of hot sauce, but forgot.  I think that might have improved the chili cheese dog a bit.  The Italian sausage was mildly spicy with very good flavor. I also had the onion rings.  I thought they were very good.  Nice strong onion taste and fresh and hot.    I was there on a Saturday morning just after 11, and there at least 15 people in line ahead of me.  That being said, the line moves fairly quickly.  They are efficient at what they do - don't wait until the last second to make your decisions.  They griller will yell out well ahead in line asking what you want.  Be prepared to yell your order out to him as he'll need to be able to hear your from a little bit of a distance.  They need to do this to get the dogs on the grill for you so that by the time you get to the condiment man, your dogs will be ready.  You'll just need to repeat your order to the condiment person so he knows which ones to grab, then you tell him what you want on each one.  Then he hands your completed order off to the cashier - and your done.  By the time I left, there were at least 30 people in line.  It's a pretty popular place - with good reason.  All the staff I interacted with were very friendly.  It's a good thing for my general well-being and overall health that this place isn't closer to me.  I would eat there a lot.  As it is, it's just far enough away that I'll go maybe once every 2-3 months.

CYBVyZ8owgBsoabMFarczA.text: Went here after stumbling home from the Tempe Beer Festival a while back - I live around the corner.   I do enjoy some char on my dogs, but I'm not as fond of the smokiness of Ted's. If you like this sort of thing, you'll love these. I'd tried Ted's once before and again, even in my inebriated state, I was thrown off a bit by it. Being from Chicago, Lobby's wins for me on the dog front. For fries, though, I'd give it to Ted's. Get them with the cheese and die happy.   I also agree with others here that there is a certain charm about the place and having staff take your order through long distance shouting as you wait in line and aren't quite certain whose turn it is.   If I was looking for a meal of cheese fries I'd come here in a heart beat. For hot dogs though I'll probably be waiting till the next beer fest.

3nFtZ9z37I-ceEcpdAS2Uw.text: I really love a good hot dog and Ted's does just about the best version of it around here.  I LOVE the hot sauce on the dogs.  The shakes are good too.  The onion rings are not my favorite they are to shoe stringy.  I prefer thicker cut onion rings.  The fries are decent.  My son LOVES the corn dogs and the white hots while my daughter prefers the foot long.

dOMUrEKazbMwVQ05-5_7GA.text: Great hotdog and good service.  Lots of condiments to choose.  It's a good place to get a quick lunch.

qkpqqOnE-lO-j-WbJSGxBA.text: Geez!  I've been dreading this review for the last couple of hours.  If this is the last review you see from me, it is because I have upset someone and they have killed me.  Cash Only? WTF! The hot dogs are barely good (flinches, looks over shoulder).  YEAH I SAID IT!  Its not so much the food I have a problem with, its the staff and the hype.  I mean, I had a feeling it wouldn't live up to the hype.  How could it?  Its a hot dog joint that has the reputation of a 5 Star restaurant.  The dogs are good. Thats it, good.  The staff and functionality of the restaurant, however, was not. Plus, they charged me for an extra order of fries! Hey! My 20 month old can't eat two orders of fries!  I ate at Ted's for lunch on Sunday with my wife.  We both got the Jumbo All Beef dog with all the toppings (Catsup, Mustard, Onions, Relish, and a Pickle)... The problem was, while in line for only 5 minutes the staff managed to screw up 3 different orders.  That was like 40% screw up!  They were not apologetic, and the customers were getting irate!  This isn't the atmosphere I look for when eating lunch.  Irate customers and hasty cooks are not a good combo.  The onion rings were just a knot of messy fried mystery.  Don't get me wrong, I ate them!  Unfortunately, I can't give this place more than 3 stars.  And with this review I will be buying a handgun for protection.

Gc0RKYZoFeOZlu6nLROclg.text: Was impressed.... At first....  Burgers are not the same.  All the dogs and brats are good, but not quite great.  Onion rings are great.  So is the setting of all the Buffalo college posters and pix on walls.  All that shines and glitters from the outside, doesn't make the dog taste better....  Great location of major cross streets.

ewWxlL50eLnGMRwkz7f_Mg.text: I feel like this is a blasphemous review, but these hot dogs are no more remarkable than what I can whip together at home. My bf and I had dinner here last night, and I had been here once before about 4 years ago. I had the all beef dog with ketchup and onions with onion rings, my bf had bratwurst and french fries, and we split a strawberry shake. The front of the counter is a little unorganized, and I can only imagine what it's like when it's busy, but the staff was nice and accurate. My bf loves this place, but the best thing about my experience was the shake.

MA_1TdG_bsrw7yxYKlb3Yw.text: Good hotdog, nice diner. Great onion rings!

GUEerroXru7r3AaZtvzQWA.text: If you have a hotdog or onion ring craving - this is the place.  The ordering process can be a bit of a new process, but in it's own way - adds to the whole fun "Ted's" experience.   Be prepared for long lines - been here numerous times and I have never witnessed a short line... take that as a good sign - great food.  Their foot longs and whitehots are great.  Onion Rings/fries with a side of cheese is a must.

-xlwLbSb8q4rNoGajbDNDQ.text: Thank god for Ted's Hot Dogs!  There is nothing better in life than a charbroiled hot dog with tasty onion rings and a soda.  My cohorts at work turned me onto Ted's and I kept it secret from my wife.  Yes, I'm that cruel.  Then one Sunday morning we were watching one of those Top 10 Hot Dog shows on the Food Network or Travel Channel.  She said to me, "I wish we could have a great hot dog today."  I broke down and wept, confessing my multiple sins of all the times I tip toed to Ted's to enjoy a chili footlong dog and an all beef dog with the works. She, loving me, immediately hit me a couple of times about the head, and said "Get dressed bitch - lunch is on you."  Now, if you ever meet Marie, you'll come to know that she is sweet and understanding, but on that day, I found one of her few limits.  Needless to say, we had a great experience at Ted's that Sunday.  REMEMBER:  They only take cash.  No debit cards, no credit cards, no bartering.

NRQLop7AKyjExb4t_cl-KA.text: Someone asked the question in the Yelp talk threads where the best place was for fried things, like french fries and onion rings.  Several people said Ted's had great onion rings......so off I went!    I expected a smaller place but I was pleasantly suprised when I pulled up to a medium sized store.  I was greated with a smile and asked what I would like.  It was a Sunday afternoon so they were not very busy.  I liked the fact that you tell them what you want and they toss it on the grill right in front of you.  Everything is freshly cooked.  They did the same with the onion rings and french fries too.  Everything was fresh and hot.  My daughter had her favorite....a hot dog, which she loved, and fries which were fresh and crisp.  I had a burger and onion rings.  Yes, the onion rings were delicious!  The batter was great and the onions were a little on the sweet side.  My burger was cooked to perfection.    This is another great little place we will go back to.  It's also sort of near my work so maybe I'll get out one day and go here for lunch.  Thanks Ted's and Yelpers!

7eErPX93DsES1vn4_ilm9Q.text: Quite a delicious all beef hot dog. I got mine with ketchup, cheese, and hot sauce. I heard the White Hot is the thing to get.

FUAHLUvBqf6I1nR4vs1trg.text: Have eaten here a couple of times.  Smell of grilled dogs fills the air and it's great.  The (basic) hot dog is pretty good.  Haven't tried the brat or other varieties yet.  But the shoestring style onion rings are the bomb!  They don't open too late to plan your dog craving accordingly.  And oh yeah, they have Buffalo and New York papers from weeks past to satisfy your curiosity of what news from the right-coast reads like.

ONl94hywJ8ozZzjFLBkl2w.text: Being from the East coast, I thought would get a nice hotdog with good chili at Ted's. Boy, was I wrong! Worst chili ever! I'd rather buy the $1.50 hotdog and soda at Costco. This meal was definitely nothing to phone home over!

5UjPI3I5loxhqjAQSbZRHA.text: Whole beef dog with everything...crusty, juicy, loaded, wow! The hot sauce here is just fiery enough to kick up the volume on that unbeatable dog. Would that I could've eaten four or five and still kept my girlish figure...

C1m0MLjiqkCuVbnps1kzJQ.text: Ok.  I'm from Buffalo.  I spent many, many drunken teenage nights at Ted's!  I was ECSTATIC to find one right here in the Valley! Sahlen's hot dogs...my mouth waters thinking about them!  They are REAL dogs, with the skin still at the ends.   When you go, ask for Weber's mustard instead of crappy French's.  Weber's is a small factory in Western NY that still does everything by hand.  It's a horseradish mustard and the best! Their onion rings are dunked and fried right in front of your eyes.  Not too much batter, and you can actually taste the onion. Expect a line.  Anytime, day or night, it's packed!  THAT is how good this place is! I love going, just to read the walls while waiting in line.   It takes me back home to Buffalo.  A place I will never in my life go visit again, but at least I can eat the food I grew up with!

LcPsftSs4vhQNorMHcqxOw.text: When I'm craving a hot dog, Ted's Hot Dogs is the place to go in Tempe. Now that sentence does contain pretty many qualifiers; I do, of course, have to be craving hot dogs; and I wouldn't drive any great distance to feed that craving.   Nonetheless, Ted's is decent for many reasons. All hot dogs and hamburgers are charcoal grilled, the sides are served in large portions, and they have many different toppings.   Now there is another very similar charcoal grill restaurant in Tempe that offers hot dogs and hamburgers -ach*chuckbox*oo- but their fare is more hamburger friendly. Ted's offers regular, foot long, and all beef franks, as well as Italian, Polish, and White Hot Sausages. Anything char-grilled is  good in my book, but the Italian sausage with peppers and onions is great. They also have the traditional toppings like ketchup, mustard, pickle, onion, tomato, etc.   The sides are dropped right when you order them, served in a basket wrapped in paper to hold it all together.  Both the fries and onion rings are good, but I prefer the fries because of the batter on the rings. While only having two side items is limited, they are a decent price.  There is one thing that I don't recommend ordering here, which is why I give them three stars instead of four. Coming from Cincinnati, one of the most important preparations of a hot dog is the chili cheese coney. I went here tonight in search of a coney similar to that of Skyline in Cincinnati: a fried dog served on a steamed bun with bean-less, finely ground chili and heaps of shredded cheese. No charcoal grilled hot dog should be covered in chili, the chili itself is pretty thick, the cheese was nacho cheese, and the hot sauce was more like salsa. I definitely will never order a chili cheese dog here again.   That being said I would point anybody in need of a grilled hot dog or sausage to Ted's.

wKn07JcfcGPR-WBq4dw20w.text: The food here was decent, but not even close to worth the ordeal that is their ordering process. You start by ordering your food at the grill, but the menu is over by the register (at the end of the line). Next, you pick your toppings, but you have to specify what meat you got (which causes a mess when the cook is trying to give the worker one thing for someone else somewhere else in the line). While this is happening, you have other people asking if you want anything to drink. Then you get to the register and have to repeat your order, while having to be sure to add sides of fries or onion rings if no one in the beginning of the line happened to ask you. Not only does this take forever but it feels like you are constantly repeating the same order to every person down the line.  Because of the constant delays in this process, the fries get double fried, the milkshakes come out runny, and you end up spending 30 minutes in line behind 3 people.  You can get food on par with this from any other burger place. I would recommend skipping the hassle and just going there.

_LwQx948ZQ0kM2hPSJsPig.text: It's been about 4 or 5 years since i was last here.  Every time I was in Phoenix area I would get lunch or dinner. Stopped in a few nights ago and it was alittle sad. The all beef hotdog was great but the regular hamburger was pretty disappointing.  It was really tiny and thin. It barely got to the edge of the small bun. Thin a regular McDonalds hamburger. The difference is that Ted's was $3.00!!! Really disappointing. The split (1/2 fries 1/2 rings) were ok but the fries were not crisp. Stick with the dogs or sausages you can find a much better burger in a lot of places. Bummer.

Uxd4drLbbUksEeyvpzdbJA.text: Best secret spot I've got yet! They've got amazing food and great service. I admit my first and second visit I didn't really know how to work the menu. But after getting to the bottom of what I wanted, it was shear pleasure from there. I knew after the first visit I'd be back for sure!

1i2fKL41aUBkYoiuHHO06g.text: My review:  Please understand that I am a hard rater.  I rarely award more than 3 stars.  My definition of 3 stars is a good, solid meal with good service.  It is a place that I recommend you try and a place I will likely return to.    The food here was tasty and the value for what you pay is within reason.  The staff was friendly and attentive.  Both made for a positive dining experience.  Tonight I had a chili dog and onion rings.  The onion rings ROCK! Yum!  Take a chance and eat here.  I think you will enjoy it.  Tell them Chris S. from Yelp sent you.  They will have no idea who the hell I am but you may get a good laugh out of it!  Enjoy!

odl6v2tcK4KTnm_8U4Qczg.text: Food is good and fairly priced.  I shared a regular hot dog topped with chili and Mac n cheese.  Also, we ordered a small fry with chili and cheese.  One thing to note is that they serve the chili and cheese on the side.  We found it a little difficult to just dip the fries since the chili is too heavy to be picked up by the fries,  I recommend just doing yourself a favor and pour the chili and cheese on the fries.    The cooks seemed a little annoyed and didn't really care to answer our questions about the menu, so I knocked off a star.  The cashier was more than accommodating though and even let us sample the Loganberry drink.  It reminds me if the juice from Ikea.  Pretty tasty!  All in all, four stars.

JGCWmPRFtFWnWDR4Rd1H6g.text: Charcoal.. sure it's a smoky flavor that makes this place special, so what, it's worth coming to.  Why, well, rats swatted off batman, as someone visiting the area, this place doesn't necessary make me want to stop; but that's probably the beauty of a shoppe that doesn't need to advertise to get it's clientele inside.   So what is it, it's a bratwurst.. maybe it's the foot long of meat.. in a tubed shape, that is shoved onto a hot charcoal grill.  Maybe it's the toppings, and all the cheese that you should also layer on top... and fries.   They also have some really good shakes and they seem to have plenty of thickness to withstand their own review.    Apparently, they are from Buffalo, NY; and the last time I was in Buffalo, I didn't try it...  but I'm glad it was on my menu of items to eat, because I think it's worth it.. and throw some chili on it too... hell, put everything on your dog... it's a meal in itself.

0GJbAS5-PuMd1APkODbIIg.text: Well, after living in Phoenix, AZ basically all of my life; I finally got to try this place.  I honestly forgot about it for a bit, but then I saw the original Ted's featured on one of the food shows.  There was a short line to begin with but didn't take long for them to get through the line.  I placed my order (with the grill master) for a Jumbo Chili Cheese Dog, onion rings, and a med drink, which he called out.  It appeared they had a system down; unfortunately, I was wrong.  They forgot to put down my order of onion rings, or it went to someone else (don't know what happened there) and then they mixed up my drink cup size, with no drink cup...needless to say I had to wait another few minutes for them to cook an order of onion rings.  Not a real big deal, other than my chili cheese dog was getting cold.  Once the order was ready though, I took it and my tray of food to a table.  The onion rings really didn't taste like they were fully cooked based on the batter consistency and it was all "clumped" together, which was a disappointment.  I was really looking forward to them, they were the shoe string type of onion rings.  The chili cheese dog was ok, I do like char-grilled hot dogs, but nothing that really stood out to me to say wow.  But the buns they use are quality ones (I believe they are the potato buns).  I wouldn't mind though going back, when I'm in the area and trying a regular jumbo dog with my choice of traditional fixings...and will go with the French fries next time.

JTCQtewVOapLZn85a2qSzw.text: This going to be a complaint. It's nice to know that an order of 20 gets preferential treatment over the rest of the lunch time crowd. I love your guys, but that is awful customer service.

-e15zGMw82KxV2XNGA7Swg.text: You wanna hot dog? This is where you get a hot dog. I was raised in Brooklyn and went to high school near Coney Island so I am well acquainted with Nathan's and this place is just as good. LOVE the onion rings and the fact they have sauerkraut for your hot dogs scores major points.

1cHwLFtcNiacuXfa542cFw.text: Don't think I have to say much about Ted's. All the bad reviews they get are by clowns that would not know a good hot dog if it slapped them in the face. wdj1KJ6iyB3p_6FVFFZ5mw.text: Good hot dog for when you're craving one. They have tons of toppings, too, including mac & cheese and bacon. Good shakes, too.

4v7QoaBGuCylrX-WyCLOzQ.text: If you're looking for comfort food, this is the place to be. I came here the other night and had a pretty damn good hot dog covered in chili and cheese. The chili was sweet and delicious, and the shakes are tasty.  I got a split (half french fries, half onion rings,) and while the fries were pretty good I just wasn't too crazy about the onion rings. They taste kind of like a bloomin' onion, but something was missing.  My advice would be if you're coming here, don't worry about the sides and indulge yourself in some delicious hot doggy goodness. I'll be back.

qZWqewkoutcZCX8MMVzF4w.text: Pretty much all of my friends that went here said it's a super delicious restaurant. After eating here, I agree with them. It is super delicious and I'd come back whenever I'm craving hot dogs, even though I ordered the bratwurst. It was not a hot dog, but I was satisfied with the taste. The sausage was cooked to perfection and the bun was soft and the peppers and onion had just enough of a sweet taste to where it did not subtract from the sausage. Great place to get a hot dog or similar. The fries were average like any other place, but they do give you a lot.  If you ever see this place, stop by and don't drive past. It's worth it.

Zga3YEzjCa2n3QlesydwsQ.text: I live super close to Ted's, and have been wanting to try it since forever because of the high ratings from Yelp and people I know. Unfortunately, it did not even come close to my high expectations.   Maybe it's because I'm not a fan of having my hot dog burnt, which I guess is what char-grilled means. Which I was unaware of how they usually cooked their hot dogs. My mistake.  The dude behind the counter grillin it up was really nice, which is why I gave it two stars. However, the wait was excruciating long for the food to taste as bad as it did. I ordered a Mac and cheese dog to go with a side of fries. I almost forgot I ordered fries because they really lacked uniqueness to me. And the dog just took over my thoughts anyway.   So it was burnt. Like I said. I had to peel off the black skin around the dog for it to be edible. Then, since I got my dog to go, by the time I got home (literally 2 minutes later) my bun was all soggy from the Mac and cheese. As a suggestion, if they order it to go maybe just put it on the side and let them put it on.   The Mac and cheese was also disappointing. I'm thinking I'm getting some actual cooked pasta, when really it tasted like easy mac. I'm a Mac and cheese lover and that was just so sad to me.   I'm really sorry that I had to write this review because I just heard amazing things about this place. Maybe it was just my experience but yeah, I won't be going there ever again.

GKO2-TU80ekQPMKLj6KuMg.text: Then very best hot dogs ever!! French fries and onion rings are incredible.  Quite th e bang for your buck. Love this place

ex8RFqziXlmvm9g2mVRDJw.text: You just can't go wrong at Ted's in Tempe. From their grilled hotdogs to their burgers. It is my go to place even with my 45 minute drive just to get my fix on twice a week.  Get whatever you want here and you won't be disappointed.

axy5LmftjxOi97ZikZYOaw.text: Ted's = The fuel that kept me running when I went to ASU.  I first came across Ted's after my classmates up'd and kidnapped me after our studio class one sunny afternoon.  I've never heard of the place and was intrigued with promises of the "best wiener you'll put your lips [Sun Devils at their prime]."  Upon entering the small establishment, the scent of meat sizzling on charcoal perfumed my senses.  I was sold.  I had the White Hot [veal and pork], a Regular with chili cheese, and a vanilla maltshake.  It was the best meal I had that long stressful year as a Digital Art major.    If this is a taste of Buffalo, I'll gladly say that I love New York!  Been a faithful customer of Ted's since that first bite~

YapQZh6_4_0PSh1mMiRj-Q.text: On the quest for the perfect hot dog, ted's fell well short of being....well, good.   Getting straight to the food: hotdogs were run of the run, and largely flavorless; mine was topped with canned/boxed agent orange Mac and cheese. Also go onion rings that were near Impossible to eat due to thin cuts, oiled out crust, and lack of seasoning.   I imagine this place is great if you are drunk, but not anything to go out of your way for.

TVZrCHOyx-zaWIv9JkgniQ.text: Ted's Hot Dogs is one of those places that just emits an aura of times long gone. When walking into this establishment I immediately heard music from the 1950s and 60s. I could smell the meat cooking on the grill and I felt like I was in another world. I looked over Ted's menu and some of the signage and became aware that this place is tied to and related to a chain of "Ted's Hot Dogs" found in Buffalo New York.   The line was fairly considerable on my initial visit and after perusing the menu I settled on an all beef hot dog, onion rings and a soft drink. With the hot dog I decided to make it as close to a Chicago style hot dog as possible. So I asked for mustard, relish,, onions, tomato, and a pickle slice.  I took the dog to an open table and dug in. The taste of the sausage here is definitely different than the steamed Chicago style dogs I'm used to. One primary reason is that everything (well all the meats) at Ted's is char grilled. This gives a nice grilled flavor to it, the actual hot dog used had an unusual filler taste with a somewhat sweet flavor rather than spicy. All things considered it was a strange mix.  The onion rings weren't so great, these were very thin onion peels deep fried. While they were plentiful there was very little onion and just lots of batter. I'd say I was a bit disappointed with them.  Since I've been in Arizona for quite a few days I did decide to return to Ted's and try things just a little differently. I went for a footlong dog which was only a little more expensive on my second visit. And rather than go for the toppings mentioned above I opted for Chili. The footlong dog was a great value and while the chilli was an extra 60 or so cents, I felt this was a much better dog than the one I ordered the first time and a lot of food for the money.  I ALSO got a regular cheeseburger, this was fairly standard and tasted like most burgers that come off of a backyard grill. Not bad, but nothing worth writing home about.  My overall opinion of Ted's is that I love the ambiance and atmosphere, the food is pretty good and it's a good value if you go for the giant footlong hot dog. I am going to give Ted's Hot Dogs four stars and a recommendation if you happen to be in Tempe Arizona.

GhU9-VPMVukyUshWwompzw.text: Family owned since 1927 in Buffalo New York they have several locations in the Buffalo area and the only out of state is in Tempe Arizona for 32 years. The hotdogs are imported from Buffalo New York they're called Salens, they also have Polish dog white hots (which is a combination of pork and veal), Italian sausage hamburgers french fries and onion rings and handmade shakes the loganberries delicious. There was a long line but the really fast all the dogs and burgers are char grill over an open flame. The grill master cool take your order on how many dogs next person will ask it what you want on it, you're hot dogs are made until you order it so you can watch the whole process, I ordered mustard chili and onions absolutely delicious my has been ordered mustard pickles and onions will ordered french fries, they have many different sauces for your fries we have the mall vinegar. Logan berry shake was perfect very thick, It just a good old-fashioned shake. Since the owners are from Buffalo New York,you'll see a lot of Western New York memorabilia. My husbands from Buffalo so having these hotdogs was very nostalgic for him. Great place to take the family.

e0BQ7cSlzpSBngIOPKYJxQ.text: This place serving all types of dogs and brats is pretty awesome in its own right, but then they go and add charcoal to cook the food and this place becomes one of the best hot dogs you will ever eat! Here is the low-down:  Good: -Charcoal grilled everything (they also have burgers and chicken) - Aunt Hattie's buns for the dogs (is a personal pref) - several types of homemade dipping sauces you won't find anywhere else to dip the fries in...some also go good on your dog - Lots of fresh toppings to choose from (lettuce, tomato, onions, pickles, relish, etc.) - Large dining area which was well kept - The bathrooms were clean and smelled good - Love how well preserved the building and signage are well kept (60's-70's era)  Bad: - While the meats are cooked to order and come out hot and fresh, my fries tastes like they had been under a heat lamp for a while and they were flimsy and cool.  Ugly: - None  Just discovered this place after living in the East Valley for almost 10 years and has instantly become one of my favorite restaurants in the whole state. Will definitely be back...and soon!

GTspMzOXNcDdiEcKlSOH4w.text: Shoot  I could have sworn I'd reviewed this place before.  I mean, it's been here a million years, and I've eaten here dozens of times. Oh well, lots of dead brain cells.  The thing I love about Ted's is they chat grill their dogs (buns too, just ask) and I like my dog burnt, like almost cremated.  Great selection of toppings, but I must (IMO) deduct one star for the chili. Just a taste thing for me, overly 'tomatoey' (like that's a word) and I like more of a spicy traditional chili. Just my opinion.  The split (half fried half onion rings) is a must side. One is plenty for two people.   We already ate half our hot dogs, so no pictures.

URExDHYo1PXwqtYLvVM9Lw.text: Growing up in the Buffalo area, Ted's was something of a staple for me. Family-owned, familiar, & quality, with roots in the area, they also make a pretty good burger & grilled chicken.  So it was a must to visit their random location in Arizona while visiting on a recent business trip.  The dining area is spacious & there's also outdoor seating for when the weather is (wait, this isn't Buffalo - it's always warm), the restaurant is clean, & the line moved quickly, so staff clearly has their act together.  You go in, you place your order & it's grilled as you go - they'll throw your burger or chicken or hot dog or whatever on the grill & by the time you've told them you want fries with that, it'll be ready for you to select your toppings.  I went with a grilled chicken sandwich, fries & of course some loganberry, in both soda & shake form.  Yes, anxious travelers from WNY, they have loganberry.  And it is good!  Will definitely return if & when I'm back in the area.

9LHLmn1-katXTJJpliM9tw.text: For a hotdog place, this is pretty good! The charcoal grilled dogs were what made the hit dogs great in my opinion. My boyfriend got the regular dog and the bratwurst dog, and I got two regular dogs and a small french fry (and a side of ranch). This did seem a little pricey to us (the total came out to be ~$18.50).   While the hotdog meat didn't blow us away (it was almost like buying regular old hotdogs at Walmart), again, the charcoaling of it was what made the meal good.   What I loved most about the meal was definitely the french fries. Something about them was just right! I wish I could have tried the onion rings, as they looked pretty good.  Being our first times there, the ordering process was kind of confusing to us. After we paid, we weren't told what we were supposed to do (ex. Wait there, go sit down and they'll bring the food over, etc.) So we elected to go grab a bench and wait. Turns out we were supposed to wait up there to then tell them what toppings we wanted on the hotdog!  Overall, this place was okay, a little expensive in my opinion for, well, a hotdog, but nevertheless, I would probably come back once or twice more if I were REALLY craving a hotdog and fries.

F2aym9HD7Lx-FxPxNA0Mtw.text: I can well imagine myself having been a regular here back in my college days had I been a Sun Devil.  Alas, I was a Lumberjack (and no I don't regret it for a second).  Ted's is the type of cheap comfort fare that unites poor hungry college kids and the general public at large.  Hot dogs, burgers, chicken sandwiches, sausages, shakes, you get the idea.  For Tempe locals and ASU alums, Ted's is an institution.  So on a Saturday at lunchtime it was time to pay homage to this local staple with a long history.  Ted's Tempe location can be found on the southwest corner of McClintock and Broadway.  I note that this is the Tempe location because Ted's is actually a chain of hot dog stands based in Buffalo, New York.  Currently 9 Buffalo area locations as of me writing this in fact.  The only non-Buffalo area location?  Right here in Tempe.  Opened almost a century ago by founder Ted Liaros, the chain is still family owned and operated to this day.  You can see that pride just walking in the door of their Tempe operation.  The place is immaculately clean and well kept.  I grabbed a spot in line as a steady stream of lunch goers walked in throughout.  The menu here is very customizable as you start your trek at the grill and tell them what kind of meat you want grilled up.  I decided to go with a suggestion listed on the "Hall of Flame" end of the menu.  A footlong hot dog coated in chili and cheese.  The dog is grilled, coated in melted cheddar cheese and topped with their housemade chili (you can opt for a bunch of other toppings as well, but I kept mine as is).  To wash down this meaty dog, I opted for a shake.  Specifically, a Loganberry (basically a hybrid of raspberry and blackberry for those not up on their plant kingdom).  Total cost for everything including tax came to about $11.  The food and beverage came out to my table in about 2 minutes.  First, the shake.  A very pleasant, creamy, slightly tart concoction.  The raspberry notes are a little more pronounced, but honestly you'd be hard pressed to find anyone who wouldn't find this a tasty treat.  Now for the footlong.  As you might imagine there's no getting around the fact that this is a messy meal.  I'm sure regulars (especially in Buffalo) would mock my usage of a knife and fork for this, but I could think of no better options.  I really liked the chili on this.  Not watered down or overdone with beans.  Just a good balance of meat, beans and sauce.  The cheese sauce and the dog itself were good, though nothing particularly special about those in my book.  Simon's in Scottsdale has been my favorite dog in town and that remains the case.  That said, for $11, I got a pretty good value.  Service was excellent, restaurant was in excellent condition as I mentioned earlier, and the shake and chili were spot on.  I'll probably try one of their burgers next time I'm here.  Or just customize my own meal, which they pretty much encourage you to do anyway.  I may not have been an ASU student, but I'm quite certain Ted's has served tens (if not hundreds) of thousands of Sun Devils over the years.  As long as they stick to their formula, they'll be around long enough to see many more generations of maroon and gold walk through their doors.

photos.caption: Photo of Ted's Hot Dogs - Tempe, AZ, United States. Loganberry shake and a footlong chili &amp; cheese dog

hXblr0y6-4rQlmyyt_Nyaw.text: These guys have great food. I didn't realize it was possible to grill on charcoal indoors, but they do, and the food is amazing. I was surprised to see that they had gluten free buns too.  The staff was really kind too.

fCmrMqRuPpVgvTDBQJMobA.text: Ted's Charcoal Grilled Hot Dogs and Burgers: a Buffalo, NY staple, also available in Tempe, AZ.   They recently remodeled this location and really provided a fresh, clean and modern feel to the dining room and menu boards. Modern decor, seating and fixtures to new digital menu boards have really freshened the place up.   As for their food, it is legit. There are not many places where you can find authentic Sahlen's Hot Dogs straight from NY, other than Ted's that is. And this isn't flame grilled over propane folks. This is grilled over smoldering coals, low and slow. Their grill masters cut the skin and roll the dogs back forth to perfectly crisp that outer casing for an amazing hot dog every time.   We had a foot long dog with chili and cheese, regular dog with cheese, kids dog w/ ketchup, a burger with American, and some french fries. The dogs were all amazing and cooked perfectly. The burger was pretty good but I definitely had some regret only getting the regular and not getting the larger patty. Need more charcoal grilled beef!!  Ted's is just like a good old fashioned backyard cookout, without having to wait for the charcoals to warm up!

photos.caption: Photo of Ted's Hot Dogs - Tempe, AZ, United States. Shoestring Fries.
Photo of Ted's Hot Dogs - Tempe, AZ, United States. Kids Dog w/ Ketchup.
Photo of Ted's Hot Dogs - Tempe, AZ, United States. Foot long Sahlen&#39;s Dog with Chili, Cheese and Onions. Amazing!

iLCWDmjHucvZjHZ0uIjepw.text: I love Ted's. It's the place to go for a quality grilled hot dog or sausage. They offer burgers and other items but I've never had them.  The basic dog is delicious. Add any toppings to personalize it to your taste. The bacon and cheese dog is decadently delicious and filling (must be all the fat from the bacon and cheese!) My husband loves the white veal dog. It is tasty! I'm partial to the Italian sausage with peppers and onions.  I Savor each bite.  The French fries are crisp, hot and not oily and they give a huge portion.  Originally from Rochester in upstate New York, Ted's has a delicious LOGANBERRY Shake. I would try it at least once. It is good!

HxwaLXd5LlsTSgpcnBTvMA.text: Well I came by for reviews... had foot long with chili cheese bacon and 1/2 fries 1/2 onion rings  Cold (not happy ) with cheese sauce. I have to say the chili was nasty.  Cheese sauce was delish. Was pricey at almost $17.00. May come back not sure. Staff really nice.

photos.caption: Photo of Ted's Hot Dogs - Tempe, AZ, United States. Chili cheese footling with bacon , 1/2 Fries 1/2 onion rings cheese dipping sauce

jl6neLwcm7e5O5bAEfSmbQ.text: This place has been around forever and was never on my radar. Seriously yummy. I was going to order the chili dog and found out that you can only have cheese sauce, as they don't serve real cheese. I was a hot pass on that, went for the ketchup, mustard, onion trio. The onion rings were awesome. My only suggestion is add shredded cheese to the menu for the chili.

rS3ZZkBF8PXyeG8nLya3Tw.text: Pretty average place  they had good reviews so I thought why not give it a try. I walk in to two employees fussing about something. One walks to the back and the other looks at me and says, "kids", when the guy looked to be about my age. Still was never greeted and it took probably about 5 minutes for the woman up front to finally ask if I was ready to order. Not a long wait which was nice but she rung me up but couldn't take my money since she was cooking- okay good job there. I get my food and the one guy still has an attitude so I see why they were arguing. They give me my food with almost not realizing I didn't pay! For a bacon hot dog, there definitely was to much bread which also seemed hard and very dry. Also the bacon nor hot dog looked burnt but tasted like it. French fries are also pretty mediocre. I don't think $10 for a foot long hot dog and fries was worth it since it tasted like a BBQ hot dog. Kinda want to come back for the drama though.

fvbZhm20ZipfbIubzF35AQ.text: Amazingly good food.  Best dog in town. Simple, great quality, awesome service.  Never a bad meal here.  Great value!!!! Very kid friendly.  Something that will be craved time and time again.  Hand battered onion rings. Yummmmmm
