Photo of Ted's Hot Dogs - Tempe, AZ, United States. All beef up top, Italian middle, Bratwurst bottom.

_xxubmi7iBCXbnNBFR9jwA.text: Basis for my starred ratings (which skews heavily to the food or drink): 1 star:  Never again. 2 stars:  Poor food, poor experience, extraordinary measures in order for me to come back. 3 stars:  Average, nothing really special, nothing particularly bad. 4 stars:  Very good, would definitely return. 5 stars:  A favorite, one of the best.  You might wonder how this place gets the same star rating from me as Steak 44 given that it's a hot dog.  I don't compare the two to each other, I compare this place to other hot dog joints.  And this is a fine example.  I love the fact that this is the only outpost not in Upstate New York.  I love the fact that they char-grill their hot dogs.  I love the variety of sausages they have.  It's not the best hot dog I've ever had, but it is mighty tasty.  I typically opt for a bratwurst with mustard and sauerkraut, or an all beef (various toppings), or the white hot (perhaps their most underrated sausage.)  The casing is great.  Even with the mauling that they do on the grill with your dog, there is still a great snap when you bite into the hot dog, and the smokiness from the charcoal is perhaps the best part of the experience.  I am not as huge a fan of the onion rings as most people are.  I like the fact that it is mostly onion - I don't like how flimsy they get most times.  I am also not a fan, generally, of their fries.  I am a fan of their milkshakes.  It is, I believe, one of the best in the Valley.  Eminently sippable (unlike the solid hunk you get at In n Out), it tastes like a classic milkshake should - ice creamy without too much ice cream, good milk, well blended.  This place is close to the perfect hot dog, but it's not quire there yet.  But rest assured you should never be disappointed for coming to a hot dog joint like this.

j4BcWBKC6810T5Jh6xRRaw.text: I had not been here since my college days and had forgotten that Ted's serves up the best onion rings in town! The rings come highly recommended with any order. We came (party of 2) on a Friday night and there was pretty much no wait. The smell of the charbroiled hot dogs definitely brought back some salivating memories. My go to is always the Classic White Hot Dog with sauerkraut, onions, mustard, and a pickle spear - pretty darn tasty. They do offer burgers, but I can never deviate from that delicious wiener in my mouth.  The service here is always quick considering they cook the food in front of you. Remember to get the rings - you will not be disappointed!

cV2y_aS9zFIXALyffVLYBQ.text: This is a great place to go for high quality char-grilled hot dogs of different varieties. It's a real show actually as the "head Char Griller" asks out loud for patrons orders in the usual long line of guests that are lined up for their food during meal periods.  You can watch your order being grilled on a huge wood burning pit as you proceed to the front of the line. The cooking aromas are intoxicating! Once there, you are asked to choose one or all toppings from a huge selection included in the price.  Pickles, onions raw and grilled, peppercini, tomatoes, marinated peppers, chili to die for, bacon (xtra $), various custom sauces, and the usual array of mustard, ketchup, pickle relish, sport peppers, celery salt, etc. etc.  Fresh house made onion rings, french fries, burgers, chicken sandwiches, and other assorted items are also on the menu. Great food and fun place too!

bj64HLEJKYHJ1xJA-ZFBhw.text: I had the jumbo all beef dog and the half and half fries and onion rings. The dog was fine I guess, but the onion rings were kinda bland and crumby.  I think this place survives on nostalgia alone.

BPdLdeHXVBOnL-lYEbKJew.text: My boyfriend and I live just a couple miles away from this place, so we've driven by it countless times. But we never stopped in because we were thinking, "It's just hot dogs, how good could it really be?" That is, until today. Being the official National Hot Dog Day we figured we'd finally give it a try - and wow, we were missing out.   The first thing we noticed was how busy it was for a weekday afternoon, with a line going nearly out the door! Even with a long line, the menu had so many choices we still hadn't decided by the time we got to the front. They had an insane amount of options just for toppings, but what immediately caught my eye was two of my favorite things in the food world - mac & cheese, and bacon. I was a little skeptical at first using mac & cheese as a topping for a hot dog, thinking it would taste really processed or too mushy like at other places, but it was absolutely delicious! My boyfriend ordered the same but got the foot-long whereas I got the regular size, and he enjoyed it just as much as I did. The only complaint we had was the price was a little expensive for what it was, but we were still fairly satisfied.  If the rest of their menu is even half as good as what we had today - there were burgers, ice cream, soups for the fall season - then we will definitely be back soon!

photos.caption: Photo of Ted's Hot Dogs - Tempe, AZ, United States. Regular and jumbo bacon &amp; mac dogs with fries.

I7rb1Z_T3bXAjh_5Mwp3zg.text: I've been eating here for quite some time. In fact, I used to work down the street a long time ago, and this is where I would lunch.  I had never been disappointed enough to review this place until recently.   We had stopped coming for a very long time since Hotdogs aren't normally in our dietary preference. However, we were seriously enwrapped in Pokemon Go, and they had a Pokemon Gym in these premises.   What a great way to enjoy a Hot Dog, and play our favorite game. We went on two consecutive occasions. Both were on a Sunday evening. Busy, but not too busy.  The first time around, the Hot Dog guy was efficient. The Onion Ring guy had a 'tude, and the cashier seemed like every customer was just a bother to her.  We both had the Hot Dogs. Mine was plain, and my wife's was the Chili Dog. We had our normal drinks, and I had a Strawberry Shake.  The Hot Dogs were just "meh" (in comparison to say, Short Leash), but everything else was okay. Nothing to write home about, and we even ignored the front desk help. We were too excited and engrossed in our Gym battles that we didn't pay much attention.  However, the next Sunday we went there. We got an even worse reception. The Hot Dog guy was on par again, but the cashier (it was a different girl, this time) was just too rude and impolite. And she forgot my wife's drink, and she threw an attitude when my wife asked for it, as if she was really being put out. I went up there and said something as I picked up the food, vowing to never to return to this establishment.  However, they left me a parting gift because the next morning, I basically heaved the Hot Dog that I ate, and everything else that came with it. I was literally sick all day, and had stomach issues for several days. And I have eaten foods in so many countries, that I don't normally react this way to bad food. Not sure if it was the Hot Dog, the Onion Rings, or the Milk Shake, but something from this place didn't agree with me to a great degree!  Hence, this will be our last visit to this Tempe icon. It has definitely fallen off our dining pedestal, and has fractured a leg!

3GmwNVwHBUmPub9u11zY0g.text: I have been here twice. The first time has a regular hot dog and a split of fries and onion rings along with a chocolate shake. OtJX4W7tFk62HoFz-F-ZCw.text: The service was good but the food was very underwhelming. I assumed that a place that specializes in charred hot dogs and burgers would actually make their own dogs OR bread and not use store bought bread and hot dogs. I literally saw them pull out the buns from a Orowheat Bag you would find in the grocery store. Buns were thin and soggy, and the hot dog was average. Tasted EXACTLY like one you can make yourself at home. The fries were ok but not very flavorful and the onion rings were gross and soggy. I was actually kind of offended when I realized we spent over $20 on a meal made of prepackaged foods from the grocery store. I do not understand why this place is so highly reviewed or why they claim to have the best dogs for 90 years. This place does not even compare to Simons Hot dogs in old town. They have fresh buns and delicious hot dogs and toppings that they make themselves instead of buying everything pre made. Defiantly will not be back.

AbAStgDfRTgNG4efwKMO0Q.text: After passing by this location so many times I finally decided to give this hot dog place a try. So I tried the regular hot dog, cheese fries, and vanilla shake for my first time. The hot dog was just okay but felt that I could have made a better choice by picking something else. Cheese fries were decent and I did like how the cheese came in a separate container cup. The vanilla shake was one of the best shakes that I've had and I have gone through plenty of milkshakes over the years in my travels. I will definitely be coming back to get that again.  There's not too much of an atmosphere here as there is more emphasis on them serving customers and it can hard to find an available table when it's busy. However this seems like a great spot for take-out as the food is prepared rather quickly. This restaurant has been here for many years and it's easy to see why it has been around for so long.

nk-IBeUXW1Utn4SDe8z3BA.text: This is a place where hot dog dreams come True. I currently have ulcerative colitis and im still going to teds tomorrow. Id rather have bad diarrhea then a bad hot dog. Portillos is a wet turd.

yGhBFfiPAt2g3n2KJu8U3Q.text: I found this place after I had been harboring a hot dog craving for a few weeks. I'm a vegetarian, and I was completely disappointed by how many restaurants in the valley do not have vegetarian options. While I do not expect a special menu for my dietary choices, it is nice to be able to go out to a restaurant with friends and not have to worry about what I can order. I found Ted's Hot Dogs after scouring Yelp for hot dog places nearby. After checking the menu of ten different hot dog places, I finally can across Ted's.   I brought a non-veggie friend to try it out. I ordered the veggie dog, and my friend and I split some fries and some onion rings. I was in heaven. The hot dog was amazing, and they dressed it up exactly like I wanted it. The fries were thin (sort of like shoestring fries), which I actually like because they're great for dunking. The onion rings, however, on my first trip were awful. They were little more than greasy onions with little batter. On my next trip, I skipped the onion rings. I'm very glad that I decided to try again, though, because when I returned to Ted's yesterday, I ordered them and they were absolutely amazing. These rings were properly breaded and they tasted perfect. I believe they're made right in the store, as they're wrapped in wax paper.  Long story short...the prices are amazing, the food is good, and this place is vegetarian-friendly. I'm very happy with this place and will definitely be returning on a regular basis.

jRGiHY9clK_EgqSuF3xV_Q.text: Love Teds hotdogs! Love that you get to watch them make everything there on the grill in front of you. I usually always get the all beef hotdog and they let you pick what toppings you want at the end. The onion rings are great!

sRc0CazrXqMn6vBx9npG0w.text: This is the go-to place to get a good hot dog. I mean we really are not flush with hot dog places everywhere you look, and they serve burgers too! Any type of sausage, dog, or brat you can think of. They grill it the way you want it too, so if you want it burnt, speak up! They use Aunt Hattie's bread which is okay in my book. Burgers, mac and cheese, hand made shacks, fresh onion rings and ice cream to rattle off a few. Plenty of help with a good attitude. Have'ta love that. Pass'n trough to...stop in.

cWSw3gsS4auwXHsVeN6xsw.text: I went there yesterday, had the White Hot and onion rings. They were so yummy.  I went today for lunch, twice. Yes, I had a Polish and Dr Pepper. It was really great. I planned to get another one, but noticed about 35 people waiting in line. I decided to wait it out, sat in my car, I needed to make some phone calls anyway.  Flash forward an hour later, the line is still around 30 people, and no, not the same people. The line is constantly flowing. I don't understand how the cook can keep track of who ordered what, but he does.  The second time around for lunch, I took an Italian dog to go. By the time I got my dog, the line was still all the way across the lobby. I saw a few people come and go without waiting, I assume that they did not want to wait.  I love how they BBQ the dog as they are ordered.  If I lived in Tempe, or even in a nearby area, I think I would go there often. I about 8 hours away. I will add this place to my list of places to go whenever in the Phoenix area.  The ONLY complaint I can find about this place is the long line. The problem with that complaint, is that the cause of the complaint is a direct result of every compliment that be made about this place.  This place kind of make think of an "American" version of Tito's Tacos (In Los Angeles on Sepulveda Place) in the aspect of simple delicious food, fast service.

21Lj8UJRmFONDj7JCm8U-Q.text: I just got done moving my kid into ASU and remembered how my father had taken me to teds so many times as a child. We got down there and waited in the usual line but it smells so wonderful with the burgers and hotdogs on the grill. The wait was very short and actually took our order as we waited in line with the tablet. Hot dogs are still unbelievably great felt like I was a little kid again. The french fries were monstrous and quantity and I got the sweet and spicy sauce which is like a fry sauce on the side went perfect with them. My wife gave me some of her onion rings to share and they were equally as good. Before I end this review I've got to say their malts are the best I've ever had outside of New York City. Even the staff came by to ask if they could take our trays for us and we're so courteous as we're getting our meal. One of the best places we're eating that in a very long time get to know the more things change the more they stay the same

OjUQ3MpIrjtzx9xk0X6xLw.text: This place has really good all beef hot dogs and burgers . The milkshakes are good too , been coming here for over 15 years. It's good to see the same guy on the grill , he's been here forever. Even though the line is usually really long , it goes by fast.

5ADMf7XsdqH8E3iG2uChnA.text: Overpriced and overcrowded for no reason. My hat goes off to Ted for whatever he is putting in the Kool-Aid, because everyone seems to think this place is a big deal.  The line is this place is always to the door and you can expect to wait 20 minutes before you even order. The prices don't match the taste, and I will never eat here again. Be prepared to drop $10 to get 1 burger and a small portion of fries.

JRWlCdB1h_1D76HMt775Kg.text: Ted's is a Buffalo institution and Tempe is very lucky to have the only out of Western New York location.  Everything is good.  I have a friend who always orders burgers and he is happy as can be (though he orders doubles because the patties are old school small and adds hot sauce).  I always order dogs.  If you want to order like a pro you could do this... wait in line , when the person grilling makes eye contact with you speak clearly your order.  If you want my advice order this way... "2 regular dogs and rings", you will then be shuffled down the line.  When they ask you how you want your 2 regular dogs I suggest this.... One with hot sauce, onions, chili and cheese, and one with hot sauce, mustard, onions, and pickle.  That is the way I have done it since I was a little kid,  This place is 5 star.

Mrkm-OHL851-BZvjv8df-w.text: This used to be my favorite place of all time. I would brag about here to friends.. "you haven't had a hot dog until you tried Ted's!!" dHjS0l7MdtKypLj3OJWBoA.text: This is my go-to place if I ever need a hot dog fix. I haven't tried the burgers, but the dogs are inexpensive, cooked over hardwood charcoal, and just plain delicious.  I think they could improve the buns that they use. I live very, very close by, but I don't come as often because the buns just don't do it for me. Growing up around Chicago, I've become very partial to the type of buns they use at Portillo's or at Hot Doug's.  Plenty of patio tables and lots of seating inside. This place is good for groups, a pair, or just by yourself but I wouldn't really call it a date spot.

wKXfALo7VEKJi3Srd0ywaA.text: This place is one of my favorites, delicious comfort foods. And I love that every time I go there I can get something different because there are so many options. I love the bratwurst and traditional hotdog. The homemade chili is great. The fries are fresh and they go great with hot cheese sauce. There are plenty of condiments to choose from and the grilled peppers and onions are fresh. They also use high-quality sauerkraut. We also have a picky eater in the family so I appreciate that Ted's has a skinless hotdog.   I appreciate the ambiance as well. It has a very authentic New York feel. And even when there is a huge line the staff is very efficient and moves through the orders quickly. You would think this may cause some mistakes but we've never had a mistake with our order, which is even more impressive considering we usually have all kinds of specialty requests and directions.   I highly recommend this place.

elTOKQu_MOLO070UNpqzHw.text: Kept hearing about this place so tried it. Food was average, price was ok, and the wait was way too long about 30 minutes for a fast casual experience. 1950's feel with 1950's food prep processes.

ijf80SNkwaIX9PM19sM_rQ.text: I've said this about Chicago vs. NY pizza and the same is True about Chicago vs east coast hot dogs.  To argue which is "better" is the same as arguing if a vacation is better in the mountains or the seashore.  WHY do people waste their time (and our time) trying to compare apples & oranges?  If you love your beloved regional favorite, why do you waste time, energy and money eating what you know you're going to hate, then waste our time rating it only a 1-star?  One such review on Yelp was one that listed their personal choice of what a Chicago hot dog is supposed to be like (while comparing it to a WNY hot dog) and "screamed" in ALL CAPS that for a real Chicago dog "NO SUBSTITUTIONS ARE ALLOWED".  Yeech.  Really?  You will only eat it the way somebody else tells you it should be eaten?  I can see why someone like that would rate Ted's 1-star.  Now welcome to Ted's in Tempe.  I'm proudly from Buffalo where Ted's was invented and still owns what a real hot dog should taste like.  I also lived in Chicago and ate those things called Chicago dogs that are boiled to the point of flavorlessness then covered with so much crap you have no idea what the hot dog tastes like.  When in Chicago, I ate as Chicagoans do and I didn't bitch and whine that their dogs didn't compare to what I was used to.  I ate them and I chose to order my own selection of condiments.  Ted's in Tempe?   Well, it is the only Ted's outside of the Buffalo, NY area, opened by Ted himself after his retirement.  Including the Tempe location they are a tiny family-owned group of Buffalo-area hot dog stands. They are absolutely True to what a real WNY hot dog tastes like and they don't wimp out and try to please the Midwesterners who wander in by mistake and think they can order a Chicago dog ... not gonna happen.  I don't have a favorite at Ted's. I am a sucker for White Hots (yeah I know, people outside of WNY have no idea what that is).  But my choice usually comes back to the footlong which is lovingly charbroiled (I know, people outside of WNY think you are a space alien if you charbroil a hot dog).  Unlike Chicagoans who were're advised like to be told how to eat a hot dog, Ted's has plenty of choices to make your dog personal.  I have my choice ... mustard, RED relish (no folks it's not hot sauce, it's a special relish unique to WNY, and it's also not chili, it's relish) and a pickle spear on the dog.  People who kill their dogs with a ton of crap should be reported to PETA ;-)  Ted's onion rings are the gold standard, and yes dang you, they are greasy like a good onion ring should be!  And I can't resist a large serving of loganberry pop (I'll wait while you Google what I mean by "pop").  People, Ted's is hot dog history and those of us who go to the Tempe location are lucky beyond words.  And (sorry if I offend anyone) but Ted's should not ever "expand" and franchise and open a location in Dubuque.  If you want the one and only you have to come to Tempe or go to Buffalo.  Otherwise, settle for what you can get elsewhere and wish you were at Ted's.

Fuck this place.

M6xkKY69Ir-XaCdL514gZw.text: Not too many Hot Dog joints around so it's easy to say it's one of the better ones. Just a little pricey (for a hot dog)... but it's a CASH ONLY place!!! 67QEInNvc_THN9MO6kWRHQ.text: I've been meaning to review this for a while now, but never got around to it.  Bottom line: Ted's is fantastic!  I'm been going for about three and a half yeas now, and Ted's has never once disappointed me.  Amazing chili-cheese dogs, brats, and polish and italian sausages.  The dogs are cooked on an actual grill too, which earns bonus points in my book .  The onion rings are also great - greasy, but in a really good way.  Definitely worth the ride out to Tempe.

d690D6EpwS6HIdwIn5-62w.text: This is the best place to get hotdogs in the Phoenix area! This is a transplant of a small Buffalo,NY hotdog chain.  The meat is flown in several times a week from Buffalo.  The dogs are great! The Weber's mustard is also a local Buffalo condiment. Don't forget the Ted's sauce on your dog too. It's basically a combination of ketchup with slightly spicey tomato relish. You can also get a foot long or a "jumbo" (really thick) hotdog. The "Jumbo" burgers are great too.  They serve Polish and Italian sausage too.  The onion rings are a great side.  You know the food is great here because there's always a line.                Be prepared to order your dogs, burgers etc while standing in line.  Don't  be one of those people that holds the line up by not having a clue what you want. If you've never been there before, read the menu posted above the grill area. You don't have to tell them the toppings you want until you reach the cash register area and your stuff is cooked.  After your order your dogs they will ask you if you want any fries or rings,  then later they will ask what you want to drink.  This type of ordering confuses some people.  It keeps the line moving, so play along and enjoy some great dogs!                                                                                                                                If you want to bring some stuff home to enjoy later, they sell the hotdogs in 5 lb bags(roughly$5 per pound.) They also sell jars of the Ted's sauce and the Weber's mustard)

9yjPuM25k3ccV9C-9b_gRw.text: I lived in Buffalo NY until 4 years old. Then moved to Scottsdale, AZ. My father turned me on to Ted's back in the 90's. He used to go to original Ted's in NY.  I've been hooked ever since. I moved to California in 1988. Every time I go back to Scottsdale my FIRST stop is Ted's. I've even called my host and said "I will be at your place in an hour. I have to get my Ted's fix!!" I will be back in Scottsdale next May, and again, my first stop will be Ted's. I keep searching, but haven't yet found a chili cheese dog as good. It's the charbroiling and the homemade relish. Rock on Ted's!!! C ya May 2010! Diane Rickmers Mitchell Cathedral City, CA

Jnk370-8cdG37ReYo-T4lg.text: OK, first things first.  To whoever even MENTIONED Pink's hotdogs in the same breath as Ted's, you are certifiably insane or you've never actually been to Pink's.  This is NOTHING like Pink's.  Pink's is like the Disneyland of hotdogs and has a wide selection of creative dogs that are worth standing in line for.  Ted's has a good solid hotdog, but definitely not worth any significant wait (which, fortunately, there was none when we went)  Mostly the options are: regular, footlong and all-beef.  Toppings were chili, cheese, ketchup, mustard (spicy and regular), onions, pickles and onions/peppers.They also have sausages (Italian, bratwurst, and others), but they weren't worth mentioning.  Definitely just get one of the hotdogs.  The buns were fresh, the onion rings are good (they're the thinly sliced, non-stiff kind) and my vanilla shake was pretty good.  But DEFINITELY not Pink's or anything amazing.  I thought Abu's review below was pretty harsh, but I hate to admit it, but he's closer to the mark than the 5 stars on here.

82CjahrTzX1ED6xxwj94Lg.text: I had an italian sausage with onions and peppers. Because I was starving, I'd say it was A-OK. Otherwise, it was pretty much a Costco sausage thrown on a charcoal grill, with onions and peppers. Which would be pretty good, actually...plus cheaper and less of a wait. It was good, but edging out Pink's? No way.
